[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Welcome to my first 1.e4 course! This course offers a full repertoire but does so without overloading you with an excessive amount of opening variations. The advantage of this course is that it offers a comprehensive set of variations and it does so in a way that develops and reinforces sound chess habits and principles  (covered extensively in my 'CPR' courses)  .     As a result, your learning will be two-fold: First, you will master ambitious opening variations; and second, you will develop a better understanding of their resulting middle game scenarios.     The Beginner's 1.e4 prides itself on being a very healthy mix of aggressive attacking systems such as the Evans Gambit, the Milner-Barry Gambit against the French, the '150 attack' against the Pirc, and most variations of the Alapin Sicilian. The course also includes some lines based on solid positional understanding such as our Alekhine lines and the Scotch Two Knights. This healthy mix was a conscious choice by me in order to maximize your growth as a chess player in every aspect of the game.   At the conclusion of each chapter, the course features an excellent selection of model games, which demonstrate the application of the discussed lines. This structured approach enables you to cement your grasp of the lines and their underlying concepts in each chapter as you work your way through the course.    The lines offered in this course have been carefully selected based on my 20 years of coaching experience as well as extensive testing both online and over the board. The quality of the chosen lines and the depth of the analysis in the course allow you to rely on this repertoire all the way to FIDE 2000-2100.  - }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Evans Gambit: 4...Bb6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ This move introduces the Evans Gambit, an opening idea that has been known since the 1820s! Evans himself was a sea Captain from Wales, and this aggressive opening idea made him eternally known in chess history.  The idea behind the pawn sac is to remove the 'piano' from the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@the word refers to 'quiet/peaceful'@@EndBracket@@ and instead, turn it into an uncompromising, aggressive gambit. Although the opening had its heyday in the 'Romantic Era of Chess', still many strong grandmasters employ it with success! }
4... Bb6 { A rather timid move, although Black's position remains solid. } 5.
a4 a5
{ This move provokes b5 but we are more than happy to oblige as it kicks out the c6-knight. }
6. b5 Nd4 7. Nxd4 Bxd4 8. c3
{ This delicious tempo negates the attack on the a1-rook and allows us to conquer the center. }
8... Bb6 9. d4
{ White has clearly won the opening battle as they have conquered the center and kept the b-pawn as well! Generally, White should continue with O-O, Be3 or Bg5 and Nd2. This position and the subsequent plans are also thoroughly discussed in the sample game section Kasparov - Piket. }
*

