[Black "Quickstarter - Evans Gambit: 4...Bxb4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ This move introduces the Evans Gambit, an opening idea that has been known since the 1820s! Evans himself was a sea Captain from Wales, and this aggressive opening idea made him eternally known in chess history.  The idea behind the pawn sac is to remove the 'piano' from the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@the word refers to 'quiet/peaceful'@@EndBracket@@ and instead, turn it into an uncompromising, aggressive gambit. Although the opening had its heyday in the 'Romantic Era of Chess', still many strong grandmasters employ it with success! }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ This is the move that earns the extra tempo for us, now we can get d2-d4 in very quickly. }
5... Bd6
{ This unattractive move is designed to provide extra security to the e5-pawn. The move leads to a solid but passive position for Black. }
6. d4 Nf6 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 { Defending e4 and reenforcing the center. } 8...
h6
{ Black should not allow the pesky pin with Bg5, but now White's development gains momentum. }
9. Nbd2 Re8 10. Qb3 { Attacking f7. } 10... Qe7 11. Bd3
{ This move is the key idea of the system: Although the bishop stands well on c4, the knight will be even better there! }
11... b6 12. Nc4 { White has tremendous pressure on Black's center. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Evans Gambit: 4...Bxb4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ This move introduces the Evans Gambit, an opening idea that has been known since the 1820s! Evans himself was a sea Captain from Wales, and this aggressive opening idea made him eternally known in chess history.  The idea behind the pawn sac is to remove the 'piano' from the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@the word refers to 'quiet/peaceful'@@EndBracket@@ and instead, turn it into an uncompromising, aggressive gambit. Although the opening had its heyday in the 'Romantic Era of Chess', still many strong grandmasters employ it with success! }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ This is the move that earns the extra tempo for us, now we can get d2-d4 in very quickly. }
5... Ba5
{ This is Black's best response. The idea is that in the case of d2-d4 the c3-pawn is pinned and so White can't achieve their dream center setup. }
6. d4
{ White goes for it anyway! The Evans is certainly not for the faint of heart, however, the invested material often leads to fabulous attacking positions. }
6... exd4 7. O-O
{ White happily gambits the second pawn in order to accelerate their development. This is an excellent representation of the Morphy principle: 'development and central control over material'. }
7... Nge7 { Black has to play with utmost accuracy! } 8. cxd4 d5
{ Again, Black's only move.   8...d6  9.Ng5!  O-O  10.Qh5  ends the game at once. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Ba3
{ Once again, our main objective is to keep the black king in the middle as long as possible. }
10... Be6 { White here has a number of interesting choices, I opted for Bb5. }
11. Bb5
{ Since d5 is very well bolstered by the black pieces, White decides to find new targets, and an additional pin is always handy. }
11... Bb4 { The following trades are more or less forced. } 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13.
Bxb4 Nxb4 14. Qa4
{ White's position is a little bit easier to play as Black still has to coordinate the defense of a few loose pieces with their king safety. }
*

