[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Two Knights Scotch #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Nf6 4. d4
{ In order to reduce the theoretical burden, I have chosen two slightly offbeat variations in the Italian @@StartBracket@@the Scotch Gambit and the Evans Gambit@@EndBracket@@. Nevertheless, these options are definitely fair dinkum ways to obtain exciting middlegame positions for White. }
4... exd4 5. e5
{ 5.O-O  is the other main variation but this line results in more exciting positions. }
5... Ng4 { It is surprisingly difficult to gain an edge against this move. } 6.
Qe2 { Defending the e5-pawn. } 6... Qe7 { Attacking our pawn once again. } 7.
Bf4 { And we defend once again. } 7... d6
{ This is Black's only way to break out of their cramped position. } 8. exd6
Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Bxd6 10. Bxd6
{ Naturally, White happily trades off the Bishops in order to mess up the Black pawn structure. }
10... cxd6 11. Na3 { Both c4 and b5 would be good squares for our knight. }
11... Nge5 12. Nb5
{ And this endgame is slightly better for White due to Black's double isolated d-pawns, one of which we shall regain soon. Currently, we are also threatening a fork on c7. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Two Knights Scotch #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Nf6 4. d4
{ In order to reduce the theoretical burden, I have chosen two slightly offbeat variations in the Italian @@StartBracket@@the Scotch Gambit and the Evans Gambit@@EndBracket@@. Nevertheless, these options are definitely fair dinkum ways to obtain exciting middlegame positions for White. }
4... exd4 5. e5
{ 5.O-O  is the other main variation but this line results in more exciting positions. }
5... d5
{ This counterthrust is always Black's best way to respond to e5, a motif you should remember as it occurs in many other openings too! }
6. Bb5
{ Both pawn captures are bad here:  ➜  6.exd6  just develops Black's pieces after  6...Bxd6  7.O-O  O-O  and Black is ahead in development as well as on material.  The d4-pawn is immune due to  8.Nxd4??  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Bxh2+  .  ➜  6.exf6?!  dxc4  7.fxg7  Qe7+  8.Qe2  Qxe2+  9.Kxe2  Bxg7  and White has a miserable position, while Black is up a pawn, and they also have the bishop pair and the more active pieces. }
6... Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ In return for the bishop pair we hope to exploit two positional factors:   ➜ The potential weakness of the dark color complex, in particular, the d4- and c5-squares;  ➜ the kingside pawn majority which is best utilized by the thematic f4-f5 plan. }
9. O-O Bc5 10. f3
{ White executes the f2-f4 idea in a seemingly delayed fashion, but in fact, playing both moves with a tempo.   The instant  10.f4  would result in the same position, but with Black to move! }
10... Ng5 11. f4 Ne4
{ The knight is now on an outpost, so one of our main strategic goals is to trade it via Nd2. }
12. Be3 Bb6 13. Nd2
{ Our best case scenario is to trade the b6-bishop and the e4-knight, thus achieving the well-known good knight vs. bad bishop situation: the blockaded c6-d5 pawns entomb the d7-bishop. }
13... Nxd2 14. Qxd2 O-O { 14...c5  will transpose into the previous line. } 15.
Nb3
{ White is slightly better due to our firm control over the dark squares. Apart from invading the dark squares, Rae1 followed by f4-f5 also looks promising. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Petroff Defense: 3...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move introduces the Petroff Defense, one of the most popular openings of our time. }
3. Nxe5
{ The most popular move and the most principled one. The e5-pawn is a vitally important central asset and if allowed, we should eliminate it instantly. }
3... Nc6
{ Introducing the very popular but perfectly unsound Stafford Gambit. Due to some popular content creators' work, this line has become one of the most popular gambits at the club level and so we need to be very well prepared. }
4. Nxc6
{ White's best move is to accept the pawn and with it the challenge as well! }
4... dxc6
{ With this recapture, Black forgoes all hopes of central control with pawns, as their e-pawn was sacrificed and the d-pawn took back on c6. Instead, Black's hopes are exclusively based on tactical tricks. }
5. d3
{ The safest way to play. Amazingly, the utterly ugly  5.f3  is also good @@StartBracket@@I even promoted that move in a video of mine@@EndBracket@@ but the text is just easier to play and looks optically more sound too. }
5... Bc5
{ Black develops the bishop and prepares a range of traps. White needs to be very cautious here! }
6. Be2
{ Not only is this a vital developing move but also a crucial defensive measure: the g4-square needed to be covered! }
6... h5 7. c3
{ This somewhat ugly move is perfectly fine here as Black also played a non-developing move  @@StartBracket@@h7-h5@@EndBracket@@. White is aiming to build a massive center with d3-d4, virtually shutting out the Black minor pieces. }
7... Be6 8. d4
{ MIssion complete! White's domination of the middle is too much for Black to handle. }
8... Be7 { 8...Bd6?  loses a piece to  9.e5  . } 9. Nd2
{ Time to complete development! } 9... Qd7 10. Qc2
{ Reinforcing e4 and thus allowing for the final phase of White's mobilisation. }
10... O-O-O 11. Nf3
{ White is dominating the game with a large center and an extra pawn. Apart from the calm Bg5 followed by O-O, White also has a promising attack after a4-b4-b5! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Petroff Defense: 3...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move introduces the Petroff Defense, one of the most popular openings of our time. }
3. Nxe5
{ The most popular move and the most principled one. The e5-pawn is a vitally important central asset and if allowed, we should eliminate it instantly. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { White's best retreat. } 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the second most popular move in this position after the main move  5.d4  . White aims to trade off the e4-knight and accelerate the development of the c1-bishop. }
5... Nxc3 { Black's most themathic move. } 6. dxc3
{ The right recapture, as it opens up the diagonal of the Bishop and offers White a semi-open file to play along. }
6... Be7
{ By far the most popular move, although it has to be stated that many other move orders are possible here. Most likely, they will transpose to our main line.  For example, at this point,  6...Nc6  first, followed by Be7, is also commonplace. }
7. Be3
{ White's main goal in this system is to quickly castle queenside and launch an attack depending on what direction the Black king chooses to go. }
7... Nc6
{ 7...d5  is too early here as White can now chip away at the central pawn easily with  8.c4!  , immediately seeking confrontation in the center. That's the right way to play! }
8. Qd2
{ White consistently carries out the intention to tuck away the king on the queenside. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ An opposite side castling scenario has occurred where, despite the material and positional balance, White has good attacking potential. }
9... Bf5 10. Kb1
{ A standard move in queenside castling scenarios. White prophylactically steps out of potential checks along the h6-c1 diagonal. }
10... Qd7 11. h4
{ And White is beginning a promising attacking operation on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Philidor Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ This is the Philidor Defense, named after the outstanding French chess player and music composer from the 1700s @@StartBracket@@also known by the name Francios Danican Philidor@@EndBracket@@. Although this defense is rather passive, due to the limited scope of the f8-bishop it should not be underestimated! }
3. d4
{ This move has been known ever since the 'Opera game' - most likely the most famous chess game ever played! White immediately challenges the center and seeks confrontation. }
3... Nd7
{ This move is the main variation of the Philidor Defense, although the capture on d4 is also a popular choice. Black opts to defend the e5-pawn without allowing their knight to be pestered.   3...Nf6  transposes into the main line after the moves:  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.Re1  c6  8.a4  . }
4. Bc4
{ This thematic developing move is very akin to the Italian @@StartBracket@@Giuoco Piano@@EndBracket@@ setups. White is aiming to cause discomfort around the weak f7-pawn. }
4... c6
{ Black's most common response in this position. The key idea is to take control over the d5-square. We already saw in the 4...Be7 line how important this can be. }
5. Nc3
{ Although  5.O-O  has a marginally better reputation, we should stick to this move as the variation most often occurs via the 'Pirc' move order, when the white knight is already committed to the c3-square. }
5... Be7
{ Black has to develop the bishop first in order to prevent the Ng5-threat. }
6. O-O
{ White completes the development of their kingside and secures the king. }
6... Ngf6
{ Black completes their kingside development as well. Although the black position may look passive, the flexible pawn formation on the queenside needs some kind of preventative measure from White. }
7. a4
{ This is it! A move whose importance is often overlooked. White drastically restricts Black's chances for a queenside expansion. Executing the desired b7-b5 break will take serious preparation by Black now. }
7... O-O { Black's kingside is fully developed albeit somewhat passively. } 8.
Re1 { White reinforces the e4-pawn and brings another piece into the battle. }
8... b6
{ Black opts to develop the bishop to b7, and also hopes to play for a b6-b5 break after preparing it with a6. }
9. h3
{ White plays a useful move and prepares for a kingside initiative once the black bishop is no longer covering f5. In the same spirit,  9.Ba2  was also recommendable.   Note that we usually very strongly disapprove of the 'bunny ears' h3- and a3-pawn moves, but here White actually benefits from delaying the development of the c1-bishop. }
9... Bb7 10. dxe5
{ Another move that breaks a number of super important principles, but it is actually a necessary preparation for a successful kingside offensive.  The plan is  10.Nh4  but without the introductory capture on e5, it just does not work:  10...exd4  11.Qxd4  d5!  and Black's counterpunch in the center comes perfectly well-timed, as the scattered white pieces are not ready for the battle. }
10... dxe5 11. Nh4
{ A very common maneuver in a number of e4-e5 openings. The idea is rerouting the knight to the f5-square, from where it exerts enormous pressure on the black kingside. @@StartBracket@@I talk about the f5-knight in great detail in my 'CPR King Safety' course as one of the most potent attackers against a short castled king!@@EndBracket@@ }
11... Nc5 12. Nf5
{ White has successfully landed the knight on the desired outpost. White's pieces are better placed and our kingside initiative is gaining momentum.  12...Qxd1  is now met by  13.Nxe7+  winning on the spot. The best way to continue our kingside aggression  is to play Qf3-g3 and then Bg5 or Bh6 even, depending on how Black reacts. }
