[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Alapin Sicilian: 2...e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... e5 { This move is actually nowhere near as bad as it looks! } 3. Nf3 Nc6
4. Bc4 Be7 { Black's safest way to develop the kingside. } 5. d4 cxd4 6. cxd4
exd4 7. Nxd4
{ Having clarified the situation in the center, White now dominates it. } 7...
Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nc2
{ This apparently unprincipled move is vitally important to retain our advantage! The purpose of the move is to gain control of the d5-square. The knight on c2 can later be re-routed to the d5-outpost via e3.   Instead,  9.O-O  Nxe4!  equalizes for Black:  10.Nxe4  d5  . }
9... Bc5 10. O-O d6 11. Be3
{ White enjoys the upper hand due to our greater piece mobility and the vulnerability of the isolated d6-pawn. White’s plan is to play Qe2 followed by Rfd1, piling up on the weak d6-pawn. Additionally, a2-a3 in combination with b2-b4 is a solid plan to gain space and eliminate the most important defender of the d6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the most commonly played move at the club level, which often leads to early opening disasters. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 Nf6
{ This is one of the many times when the knights can be kicked around by central pawn thrusts, something we should always consider a top priority whenever doable. }
5. d5
{ Only this way! It is important to stop the knights from becoming effective blockaders, e.g. after  5.e5?  Nd5   the central pawns have become rigid, and we can no longer hassle the knights. }
5... Ne5 6. f4
{ Now the pawns keep on rolling forward, conquering the entire center and pushing the cavalry back all the way. }
6... Ng6 7. e5 Ng8 8. Nf3 { White's central domination is simply unbearable. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ This move challenges the e4-pawn just like the 2...d5 line which is the other most principled response to the Alapin. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3
{ White is no hurry to recapture on d4. In fact, we are happy to jettison a pawn to accelerate our development. }
5... Nc6 6. Bc4 { Once again, we prefer develpment over recovering material. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 d5
{ This move is essentially the same as  7...d6  , as we will take the pawn in either case. }
8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O
{ True to our chess philosophy, we prefer development and piece mobility to material, so we delay the recapture on d4. }
9... Be6 { This is Black's best and most popular choice here. } 10. Bxe6 Qxe6
11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4
{ This is the less trodden path by theory, but the one carrying more venom! Now, our main focus is to hit Black before they can finish development and castle. }
12... Qd7 13. Nc3 Rd8 { Attacking our d4-pawn. What to do? } 14. Re1
{ As always: 'Initiative over material' is our motto. } 14... Qxd4
{ Or  14...e6  15.g4  and Black has difficulty developing the f8-bishop. } 15.
Qf3 Rd7 16. Bg5 { White has a huge attack against the uncastled black king. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Alapin Sicilian: 2...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black manages to deny White a wide center but at the cost of bringing the queen out too soon! }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is the major junction here. Black has multiple choices, the two most popular ones being Bg4 and e6 but we will have a look at other options, too. }
5... Bg4 6. dxc5
{ Although the most popular move here is  6.Be2  , this capture is a far more fun and lively variation! }
6... Qxc5
{ The endgame variation with  6...Qxd1+  is quite similar to the line arising after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  Nf6  5.Nf3  e6  6.Be3  Nc6  7.dxc5!  Qxd1+  8.Kxd1  etc. }
7. Na3
{ This knight move introduces various attacking schemes based on the Nb5 follow-up, but after the often played a6, the cavalry can become very effective on c4 too! }
7... a6
{ Black eliminates the Nb5-threat but in doing so weakens the b6-square. } 8.
h3
{ Before we kick the Queen, it is wise to query the intentions of the g4-bishop as almost every response will have its drawbacks. }
8... Bh5 9. g4 Bg6 10. Be3 Qc7 11. Bg2
{ White is way ahead in development and is now ready to take advantage of the immobile black pieces. }
11... e6 12. Qa4+ Nbd7 13. Bf4 Qc8 14. Ne5
{ White has a pleasant edge due to their greater piece mobility and better central control, as was seen in Sveshnikov - Gashimov, Dubai 2003. White’s goal is to play Rd1 and delay Black’s castling for as long as possible. O-O followed by doubling on the d-file would create unbearable pressure on Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - French Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense is a slightly passive but certainly very solid opening choice that has been known to be a reliable choice for Black ever since Paul Morphy! }
2. d4 d5
{ There are many ways to play against the French. Among them, the best established are  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  . These variations, however, require a lot of time and effort to master. Our choice is simpler, but nonetheless very exciting! }
3. e5
{ This move introduces the Advance Variation. White immediately grabs the offered space and restricts the black army.   This structure is usually founded on a simple strategy for both sides: Black aims to undermine the center with c7-c5 and f7-f6. White, in turn, tries to retain the center and the pawn chain as best as they can. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6
{ This is Black's most thematic move, immediately pressuring the d4-pawn and keeping an eye on b2 as well. }
6. Bd3
{ This cheeky developing move introduces the Milner-Barry Gambit. White opts to develop the bishop to the most appropriate diagonal, however, it comes at the cost of weakening the d4-pawn. }
6... Bd7
{ This developing move indirectly threatens the d4-pawn since now there is no discovered check with Bb5+ after  7.--  cxd4  8.cxd4  Nxd4  9.Nxd4  Qxd4  .   6...c4  is a very common mistake at the club level. Black releases tension in the center and gives White a free hand to develop. In the ensuing, tightly closed position White's kingside attack develops naturally while Black will struggle to find counterplay. }
7. O-O
{ In essence, this is the real gambit move. White jettisons the d4-pawn in order to accelerate development. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Nxd4
{ Black's best choice is to actually accept the gambit. Everything else is inferior: }
9. Nbd2
{ This move keeps things a bit more complicated than the other line with  9.Nxd4  . }
9... Bc5 10. b4
{ We should not hesitate to throw more logs onto the fire! This move allows us to keep the momentum by disallowing the completion of Black's development. }
10... Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3
{ This novelty is actually a key component of the line. In order the understand this move we need to appreciate Black's defensive idea against  11.Nxf3  which leads to a slightly worse endgame after  11...Qxb4  12.Rb1  Qa4!  @@StartBracket@@the key idea of the defense@@EndBracket@@  13.Qxa4  Bxa4  14.Rxb7  Ne7  and White's counterplay fizzles out. }
11... Qxb4 { The only way to capture. } 12. Rb1
{ This move is a well-deserved reward for the 10.b4 sacrifice! Not only do we score yet another tempo on developing, but the rook also aims at a very important target, the b7 pawn! Once on b7, the rook becomes a very annoying attacker along the 7th rank! }
12... Qa4 13. Rxb7 { Our rook already reached the 7th rank. } 13... Ne7 14. Qg3
{ Putting pressure on the g7-pawn. } 14... O-O 15. Nf3
{ White has a nicely developing attack on the kingside, whilst the black army is somewhat tied down by the rook on the 7th. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter -  Caro Kann: 4...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This move leads to two very different positions, depending on how Black retakes on f6. }
5. Nxf6+ exf6
{ This move is the less ambitious but more reliable one, endorsed by the legendary opening expert Erwin l'Ami. Black entirely gives up the idea of fighting for the center in order to establish an extremely safe and robust layout. }
6. c3
{ This strange move is required before White plays Bd3-Ne2 - the best layout in this pawn structure.  If  6.Nf3  the knight does not stand well here due to the fact that it is restricted by the f6-pawn.   6.Bc4  leads to a famous blunder:  6...Qe7+  7.Ne2??  Qb4+  . }
6... Bd6 7. Bd3
{ White begins developing their pieces to the most natural squares. } 7... O-O
8. Qc2
{ This annoying move forces Black to defend h7 instead of continuing to develop their pieces. }
8... Re8+
{ The rook develops with a tempo, but White also wants to put the knight on e2 anyway, so this is hardly a concern for us. }
9. Ne2 h5
{ This wild-looking thrust is actually the newest trend! Black is not shying away from lunging forward, hoping to soften White's kingside with a further h5-h4-h3! }
10. Be3
{ White finishes development with this natural move. The general goal upon completing development is to try to trade down to an endgame where the queenside pawn majority can become a decisive factor. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O
{ 11.O-O-O  was tested between Duda and Carlsen but here Black seems to have plenty of play after the thematic  11...b5! }
11... h4 12. h3
{ White should not allow the pesky h-pawn to march all the way to h3. That said, after 12.h3 White has to be a little bit careful with the threats on the h2- b8 diagonal. }
12... Nf8 13. Rad1 Bc7 14. c4
{ White has accomplished most of our goals: Development is complete and the d4/c4 central formation has been achieved. From here on, we aim to trade pieces and utilize our mobile queenside pawn majority. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter -  Caro Kann: 4...Nd7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ This line is called the Karpov Variation, named after the World Champion who employed it frequently at the top level. The idea is to offer a trade on f6 without having to compromise the pawn structure. }
5. Ng5
{ An unorthodox move in return. As the c8-bishop has been blocked in, White is trying to generate tactical opportunities on the light squares, in particular on f7 and e6. Black needs to play very precisely to avoid all the pitfalls lurking in the next couple of moves. }
5... Ngf6
{ 5...e6  is also a perfectly sound move that is going to transpose after  6.Bd3  Ngf6  . }
6. Bd3
{ This is the right square for the bishop, as it allows us to retain our Ne6 ideas. }
6... e6 7. N1f3 Bd6 8. Qe2
{ White is keeping all options open and prepares to castle queenside. } 8... h6
9. Ne4
{ This retreat is necessary now as the e6-sacrifice no longer works due to Black's improved development. }
9... Nxe4 10. Bxe4
{ This is not the main move, however, we should prefer it because there is little to be gained by engaging with the jungle of variations after  10.Qxe4  . }
10... Qc7 11. Bd2
{ Completing the development of the minor pieces and still keeping Black guessing about which way we are going to castle. }
11... b6
{ This is the best way to develop the c8-bishop and this way Black also keeps their castling options open. }
12. O-O-O Bb7 13. Kb1
{ This prophylactic move secures the king firmly and forces Black to reveal their castling intentions. }
13... O-O-O 14. c4
{ A typical measure to gain space before Black achieves the c6-c5-break. }
14... Rhe8 15. Bc3
{ White enjoys the upper hand due to our greater mobility and space advantage. Neither Black breaks @@StartBracket@@c5 and e5@@EndBracket@@ can be played without creating further weaknesses. White should aim to increase the pressure along the e- and d-files by playing Rhe1 and Bc2. Once it is accomplished, the Nd2-e4 maneuver could be considered. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Caro Kann: 4...Bf5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This move introduces the Caro-Kann Defense, an opening named after two 19th century masters, hailing from England and Austria, respectively. This opening is known for its reliable, sturdy layout and was a preferred choice for many World Champions including Capablanca, Petrosian, and Karpov. }
2. d4
{ As always, when given the chance, we should grab the center with both pawns! }
2... d5 3. Nc3
{ The most thematic response: White develops a piece and retains the central tension. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5
{ The most popular variation, which was popularized by Capablanca, the legendary Cuban World Champion. Ever since, it has been known as one of the most reliable defenses against 1.e4. }
5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4
{ This move tickles the bishop and intends to secure some space advantage on the kingside. }
6... h6 7. h5
{ This pawn thrust has a long-term benefit too: the h5-pawn restricts the g7-h6 pawn duo, which often becomes a meaningful trump card in various endgame scenarios. }
7... Bh7 8. Nf3 e6 9. Bd3
{ The active 'Capablanca bishop' needs to be dealt with. This move also helps us to find a good square for our queen, which paves the way for queenside castling. }
9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nd7 11. Bd2
{ 11.Bf4  is also possible here, but  11...Qa5+  usually forces the  bishop back to d2 anyway. }
11... Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Qe2
{ This useful move removes the queen from the d-file, allowing our rook to operate more efficiently against c6-c5 breaks. Also, White is now prepared to occupy the center with Ne5. }
13... O-O 14. Nf1
{ With Black having committed to opposite side castling, we adjust our plans! This counter-intuitive knight move prepares a major assault on the kingside.   White's plan is simple yet super effective: g2-g4-g5, attacking the enemy king @@StartBracket@@even at the cost of a pawn or two!@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Modern Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ This is the so-called Modern Defense, which very often transitions into the Pirc. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3
{ With this move, we steer the game towards a familiar setup and encourage Black to transpose back to the Pirc lines with Nf6 or c6. }
4... a6
{ This is the only noteworthy move in this variation that gives the position a different character compared to the Pirc main lines. }
5. Qd2 b5
{ Compared to the Pirc lines where Black plays c6, the a8-h1 diagonal is now open. It gives Black different options. }
6. f3 Bb7 7. g4
{ This move has multiple benefits. It restricts Black's h7-h5 ideas and it also discourages Nf6.  Instead, if  7.h4  h5  8.Nh3  Nf6  9.Ng5  Nbd7  it is unclear how White can accomplish anything on the kingside and in the center. }
7... Nd7 8. O-O-O Ngf6 9. Kb1
{ This prophylactic move secures the queenside. No matter what Black does now, White will have an adequate answer. }
9... c5 10. h4 { White carries out the usual kingside attack. } 10... h5 11. g5
Nh7 12. dxc5 { White can now open up the position favorably. } 12... Nxc5 13.
Bd4 O-O 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Nge2
{ White has a really good position. The h7-knight is a particularly sad sight. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Pirc Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ Technically speaking, this move followed by g6 introduces the Pirc. That said, there are a huge number of move order tricks available for Black very early on that may confuse the unsuspecting White player. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Note that  3...e5  transposes back to the Philidor Defense after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  c6  . }
4. Be3
{ This bishop move, usually followed by Qd2, is the backbone of our setup. The idea is to trade the g7-bishop via h6. }
4... c6
{ In my opinion, this is the most clever way for Black to play. The idea is that Black will not lose a tempo by playing Bg7 and then having to take on h6. }
5. Qd2 b5 { Black immediately begins their queenside counter-offensive. } 6.
Bd3
{ In response, White keeps their options open in regard to castling and instead focuses on completing development. }
6... Nbd7 7. Nf3
{ We are threatening the typical e4-e5 break and so Black's options are limited. }
7... e5 8. O-O
{ Here it is tempting to make one of the most commonly occurring positional mistakes by taking with  8.de5?   Don't do this! White gives up the center,  and relinquishes the c5-square to the black minor pieces for no return at all. }
8... Bg7 9. a4
{ It is in our interest to generate as much tension as possible, seeing that our army is far better prepared for battle. }
9... exd4 10. Nxd4 b4 11. Na2
{ Black has difficulty hanging on to both c6 and b4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Scandinavian: 2...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ This move introduces the  Portuguese Gambit, which is a popular choice of many club-level players. }
3. d4
{ White simply gets on with their usual agendas  @@StartBracket@@center and development@@EndBracket@@, instead of trying to keep the d5-pawn, which can indeed lead to some really unpleasant and complicated scenarios. }
3... Nxd5 4. Nf3 g6 5. c4
{ This natural space grab is our bread and butter in this system, allowing us to secure a pleasant space advantage. }
5... Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. c5
{ At first, this move is a positional mistake as it hands over the d5-square to Black. Upon deeper analysis, we will see that Black can't keep the d5-square without serious concessions. }
7... Nd5 8. Bc4 c6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1
{ Playing natural developing moves is something I like to put heavy emphasis on. You'll find that in most openings @@StartBracket@@even if you are on alien territory@@EndBracket@@, healthy, simple moves are almost always the best! }
10... Bg4 11. Bg5
{ And White has the upper hand due to the pressure on the e7-pawn and better development. Our goal is to increase the pressure by kicking the g4-bishop with h2-h3 followed by Qb3 and Rad1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Scandinavian: 2...Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qd8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 { We immediately attack the queen. } 3... Qd8
{ This is a very passive move that allows us to freely develop and occupy the center. }
4. d4
{ Whenever the opportunity arises to conquer the center, we should take it! }
4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3
{ While the pin poses no threat, chasing the bishop around allows us extra tempi to develop and gain momentum on the kingside. In the meantime, Black loses valuable time that they could have spent developing the rest of their army. }
6... Bh5 7. g4
{ This expansion, featured in many other variations in this course, is almost always unpleasant for Black. The bishop is constantly under threat, whilst White's kingside initiative develops nicely. }
7... Bg6 8. Ne5
{ The knight is perfectly placed in the center and White is now adding h4-h5 to the equation. }
8... e6 9. Bg2 c6 10. h4 Bb4
{ Black hopes to use the pin to evacuate their nearly trapped g6-bishop via e4. }
11. O-O Nbd7 12. Qe2
{ Black has nothing against the incoming h4-h5:  12...h6  13.Nxg6  fxg6  14.Qxe6+  with a winning attack. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Scandinavian: 2...Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qa5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 { We immediately attack the queen. } 3... Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5.
Nf3 c6 { 5...Bf5  6.Bd2  c6  transposes. } 6. Bd2
{ We eliminate the pin and create a discovered attack threat against the queen. }
6... Bf5 7. Ne4
{ The idea is to trade on f6 and damage Black's pawn structure. } 7... Qc7 8.
Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Just like in the Caro-Kann Nf6 line, here too, Black can take either way, with very similar structures and ideas. }
9. g3 { 9.Bc4  is also popular here but the text offers more. } 9... e6 10. Bg2
Nd7 { Black wants to castle queenside. } 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Re1 Bd6 13. c4
{ White has a comfortable edge as our queenside prospects are much better than Black's chances on the other wing. This was played in Glek - Nakamura 2003, Minneapolis. Apart from the indicated c4-c5 plan, White should consider Qa4 and b2-b4-b5 to enhance the attack. }
