[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Quickstarter - Alekhine's Defense"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ This slightly provocative knight jump introduces the Alekhine Defense - named after the 4th World Champion. Black's idea is to provoke an overextension in the center, which they can then undermine. }
2. e5
{ The principled response. If an opponent's knight can be kicked, it is almost always the right response! }
2... Nd5 3. d4 { Centah! When space is offered, we should grab it. } 3... d6 4.
c4
{ The other main theoretical line begins with  4.Nf3  , leading to classical variations. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ The text aims to resolve the battle for the center immediately. Although White does give up the e5-pawn, the d4-c4 formation allows White to remain dominant in the middle. }
5... cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3
{ White is following a unique method of development in this line. The idea is to completely mobilize and fortify the queenside in order to prepare for Black's thematic e7-e5 break. }
7... Bg7 8. Rc1
{ White removes the rook from the scope of the g7-bishop. The delayed development of the kingside here is not that pressing as Black is also undeveloped on the queenside. }
8... O-O 9. b3
{ The final step of bolstering the center.  The variation after  9.Nf3  d5  10.c5  Nc4  demonstrates  why the b2-b3 push is necessary. White has to part with one of their bishops. }
9... e5 { Interestingly, Black does not really have anything else available! }
10. dxe5
{ White is aiming to play an endgame in which their queenside pawn majority and space advantage can become decisive advantages. }
10... dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. c5
{ Forcing Black to move backward, hindering their own development and also making space for Bc4. }
12... N6d7 13. Bc4
{ This natural developing move helps us control the d5-square and also attacks f7. }
13... Nc6 14. Ne4
{ The pending Ng5 and Nd6 threats make White's position easier to play, while Black's army remains uncoordinated. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit: 4...Bb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ This move introduces the Evans Gambit, an opening idea that has been known since the 1820s! Evans himself was a sea Captain from Wales, and this aggressive opening idea made him eternally known in chess history.  The idea behind the pawn sac is to remove the 'piano' from the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@the word refers to 'quiet/peaceful'@@EndBracket@@ and instead, turn it into an uncompromising, aggressive gambit. Although the opening had its heyday in the 'Romantic Era of Chess', still many strong grandmasters employ it with success! }
4... Bb6 { A rather timid move, although Black's position remains solid. } 5.
a4 a5
{ This move provokes b5 but we are more than happy to oblige as it kicks out the c6-knight. }
6. b5 Nd4 7. Nxd4 Bxd4 8. c3
{ This delicious tempo negates the attack on the a1-rook and allows us to conquer the center. }
8... Bb6 9. d4
{ White has clearly won the opening battle as they managed to conquer the center and keep the b-pawn as well! Generally, White should continue with O-O, Be3 or Bg5 and Nd2. This position and the subsequent plans are also thoroughly discussed in the sample game section Kasparov - Piket. }
*

