[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit: 4...Bxb4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ This move introduces the Evans Gambit, an opening idea that has been known since the 1820s! Evans himself was a sea Captain from Wales, and this aggressive opening idea made him eternally known in chess history.  The idea behind the pawn sac is to remove the 'piano' from the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@the word refers to 'quiet/peaceful'@@EndBracket@@ and instead, turn it into an uncompromising, aggressive gambit. Although the opening had its heyday in the 'Romantic Era of Chess', still many strong grandmasters employ it with success! }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ This is the move that earns the extra tempo for us, now we can get d2-d4 in very quickly. }
5... Bc5
{ This move is just entirely playing to White's hand by allowing d2-d4 with a tempo. }
6. d4 exd4 7. O-O dxc3
{ A common blunder in this @@StartBracket@@and in similar@@EndBracket@@ positions. GM John Nunn's axiom - Loose Pieces Drop Off - comes to mind as we execute the following tactic. }
8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. Qd5+ { The bishop is the loose piece. } 9... Kf8 10. Qxc5+ d6
11. Qxc3
{ White is much better as Black will find it very tough to secure the king. After completing development with Nbd2 and Bb2, White's goal is to crack the position open with the standard e4-e5 break, in order to further expose the opponent's king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit: 4...Bxb4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ This move introduces the Evans Gambit, an opening idea that has been known since the 1820s! Evans himself was a sea Captain from Wales, and this aggressive opening idea made him eternally known in chess history.  The idea behind the pawn sac is to remove the 'piano' from the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@the word refers to 'quiet/peaceful'@@EndBracket@@ and instead, turn it into an uncompromising, aggressive gambit. Although the opening had its heyday in the 'Romantic Era of Chess', still many strong grandmasters employ it with success! }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ This is the move that earns the extra tempo for us, now we can get d2-d4 in very quickly. }
5... Bc5
{ This move is just entirely playing to White's hand by allowing d2-d4 with a tempo. }
6. d4 exd4 7. O-O d6 8. cxd4 Bb6 9. Nc3 Na5
{ It is vitally important for Black to kick out the well-placed white bishop.   9...Nf6  allows White to demonstrate how brutal life can get in the Evans Gambit:  10.e5  dxe5  11.Ba3!  @@StartBracket@@this motif never gets old!@@EndBracket@@  11...Nxd4  12.Nxd4  Bxd4  13.Nb5!!  @@StartBracket@@White disregards all material considerations and instead fully focuses on the vulnerable black king@@EndBracket@@  13...Bxa1  14.Qxa1  and despite the large material discrepancy White is completely winning. The black king is stuck in the middle forever and due to the undeveloped black army, it actually feels as if White was up material, not down! }
10. Bd3 Ne7
{ Black cleverly avoids  10...Nf6  , which again would be very effectively met by  11.e5  . }
11. h3
{ One of the few occasions when the bunny ears are justified! By eliminating Bg4, White eliminates any kind of active play by Black and can rely on their positional trumps: the dominant center and the better piece coordination and development. White’s already impressive piece layout can easily be improved upon by Bf4-Qd2-Rfe1-Rad1 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Evans Gambit"]
[Black "Evans Gambit: 4...Bxb4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Bc5 4. b4
{ This move introduces the Evans Gambit, an opening idea that has been known since the 1820s! Evans himself was a sea Captain from Wales, and this aggressive opening idea made him eternally known in chess history.  The idea behind the pawn sac is to remove the 'piano' from the Giuoco Piano @@StartBracket@@the word refers to 'quiet/peaceful'@@EndBracket@@ and instead, turn it into an uncompromising, aggressive gambit. Although the opening had its heyday in the 'Romantic Era of Chess', still many strong grandmasters employ it with success! }
4... Bxb4 5. c3
{ This is the move that earns the extra tempo for us, now we can get d2-d4 in very quickly. }
5... Be7 6. d4 { Going for our central formation. } 6... Na5 7. Be2
{ White retreats all the way in order to allow the queen to keep an eye on the d4-pawn. }
7... exd4 8. Qxd4
{ This slightly surprising recapture is the reason why White wanted to keep the d-file open. By taking with the queen, we gain an important tempo and now Black's development becomes more problematic. }
8... Nf6 9. e5
{ 'If a developed knight can be kicked, it is almost always the best move' says chesscoachandras all the time! }
9... Nc6 10. Qh4
{ Although Black scores a fair few tempi on attacking the queen, the knight moves are also costly time-wise. Additionally, the queen will end up on g3, a nice square to pressure the kingside! }
10... Nd5 11. Qg3
{ Black has an awkward choice to make now as  11...O-O  loses to  12.Bh6! }
11... g6 12. O-O
{ White has a lovely position here with a lot of play around the weak dark squares. Also, note that the development of the black queenside is rather difficult to obtain. Our model gameKasparov - Anand demonstrates the above claims beautifully. }
*

