[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.1) Evans Gambit - Model Games"]
[Black "M. Vachier Lagrave - Wesley So (online blitz), 2019 "]
[Result "*"]

{ I decided to include this game in the game selection despite the very short time control. The reason is that the game is full of highly educational attacking ideas and motifs. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 exd4 7. O-O Nge7 8.
cxd4 d6
{ Wesley blunders very early on. This being an online game, however, it could have been a mouse slip.   8...d5  is our main theoretical line. }
9. Ng5 d5 { A sad necessity as castling loses instantly:  9...O-O  10.Qh5  . }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxf7
{ A well-known motif from the Fried Liver Attack. The black king will be stuck in the middle, facing White's mounting attack. }
11... Kxf7 12. Qf3+ Qf6
{ If  12...Ke6  then  13.Nd2!  develops a piece and shields the e1-square for the imminent rook check.  After  13...Ncb4  14.Re1+  Kd6  15.Bb5!!  this sensational move actually leads to a mate in 5, no matter what:  15...c6  16.Nc4+  Kc7  17.Qg3+  Kd7  18.Qd6 }
13. Bxd5+ Ke7 14. Qe4+
{ A blunder, in turn, from the Frenchman. The following lovely sequence would have netted a piece instantly:  14.Bxc6  Qxc6  15.Qa3+  . }
14... Kd8 15. Be3 Bf5 16. Qf3 Bb6 17. Nc3
{ With his king hopelessly stuck in the middle, Black has very little to hope for. }
17... Bg6 18. Qg3 Qd6 19. Bf4 Qd7 20. Rfe1
{ White, of course, happily abandons the d4-pawn as its capture would open up another avenue for the attack. }
20... Nxd4 21. Rad1 Re8 22. Rxe8+
{ 22.Bxb7  would have won on the spot:  22...Rxe1+  23.Rxe1  Rb8  24.Bg5+  . }
22... Qxe8 23. Be5 c6 24. Bc4 Qd7 25. Bxd4 Bxd4 26. Qh4+
{ And White went on to win later on... } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.1) Evans Gambit - Model Games"]
[Black "G. Kasparov - J. Piket, Amsterdam 1995"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bb6 5. a4 a5 6. b5 Nd4 7. Nxd4 Bxd4 8. c3
Bb6 9. d4 exd4 10. O-O
{ Kasparov plays the opening in its right spirit, leaving the pawn hanging and focusing on rapid development. }
10... Ne7 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxe7
{ Retaining the pin with  12.Bh4  is also thematic. } 12... Qxe7 13. cxd4 Qd6
{ Although the engine does not disapprove of this move, it does look extremely ugly. To a human eye, d7-d6 appears far more natural:  13...d6  14.Nc3  Be6  15.Nd5  Bxd5  16.Bxd5  and White still enjoys the upper hand. }
14. Nc3
{ Being true to his idols, Morphy and Alekhine, Kasparov prefers dynamic piece play to material. }
14... Bxd4 15. Nd5
{ Inspired chess! Black is gradually trading away all his developed pieces and will be left with the well-known 'back-rank-fest'. }
15... Bxa1 16. Qxa1 O-O
{ 16...f6  is a typically ugly engine move. Yet, it is the only one that keeps Black in the game. }
17. e5 Qc5 18. Rc1
{ The contrast between the two armies could not be more striking. White's army is fully mobilized and operational, whereas Black is dancing around with a sole queen. }
18... c6 19. Ba2 { And the days of the queen are numbered. } 19... Qa3
{ 19...Qa7  leads to two marvellous variations:  20.b6  Qb8  @@StartBracket@@  20...Qa6  21.Bc4!  and the queen is trapped@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rqb2rk1/1p1p1pp1/1Pp4p/p2NP3/P7/8/B4PPP/Q1R3K1 w - - 1 21@@EndFEN@@  21.Nc7  with complete entombment of the queenside. }
20. Nb6 { And now Black loses material due to the dual threat. } 20... d5 21.
Nxa8 Kh8 22. Nb6 Be6 23. h3 Rd8 24. bxc6 bxc6 25. Rc3 Qb4 26. Rxc6 Rb8 27. Nxd5
Qxa4 28. Rc1 Qa3 29. Bc4
{ A stunning victory by Kasparov, in the style of the romantic greats! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.1) Evans Gambit - Model Games"]
[Black "G. Kasparov - V. Anand, Riga 1995"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4
{ Kasparov boldly invites the Evans again in the same year, and this time against a future world champion! }
4... Bxb4 5. c3 Be7 6. d4 Na5 7. Be2 exd4 8. Qxd4 Nf6 9. e5 Nc6 10. Qh4 Nd5 11.
Qg3 { Until this point, we follow the main line of the course. } 11... g6
{ Or  11...O-O  12.Bh6  . } 12. O-O Nb6 13. c4
{ Utilising his space and development advantage, Kasparov prepares his whole army for the attack. }
13... d6 14. Rd1 Nd7
{ Another 'chesscoachandras mantra' goes: When you are going backward, you are almost certainly doing something wrong...   14...Na4!?  is the only way to stay in the game, as this move holds c4-c5 without compromising development. }
15. Bh6
{ As usual, Kasparov pays no heed to material considerations and goes for the throat! }
15... Ncxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Nc3
{ The black king is a sitting duck and it is only a matter of time before Kasparov breaches the defense. }
17... f6 18. c5 Nf7 19. cxd6 cxd6 20. Qe3 Nxh6
{ Although this move eliminates the pesky bishop, the invading queen is a far more dangerous intruder. }
21. Qxh6 Bf8 22. Qe3+ Kf7
{ 22...Qe7  is hardly an improvement due to  23.Qf3!  . } 23. Nd5
{ Black is falling apart on the light squares. } 23... Be6 24. Nf4 Qe7 25. Re1
{ And Black threw in the towel as the e-file pin decides the game:  25...Bh6  26.Bc4!!  or @@StartFEN@@r4b1r/pp2qk1p/3pbpp1/8/5N2/4Q3/P3BPPP/R3R1K1 b - - 8 25@@EndFEN@@  25...d5  26.Bf3  Bf5  27.Bxd5+  Kg7  28.Qxe7+  and White is winning. }
*

