[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Two Knights Scotch"]
[Black "Two Knights Scotch #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... h6
{ A really poor move that betrays both central control and development, but since it is the third most popular move at the club level, we should briefly attend to this. }
4. d4
{ Poor moves almost always get punished in the center! With this move, White immediately wants to grab the initiative and the central control. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White is basically playing a Four Knights Scotch with the inserted Bc4 and ...h6, which, of course, heavily favors White. }
6... Bb4 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5
{ White is ready for confrontation, Black is walking on thin ice. All the popular moves in the lichess database lead to hopeless positions here. }
8... Nd5
{ 8...Ne4  is the most popular.  9.O-O  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bxc3  11.Qf3!+-  This double attack is immediately decisive. }
9. O-O
{ Among the many good moves this is the most thematic, focusing on development and ignoring the material! }
9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Qf3
{ White's advantage is clear: The two bishops are super powerful and Black is struggling to mobilize. Our main plan is Qf3-g3, Bd3, c4 etc. }
*

