[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Two Knights Scotch"]
[Black "Two Knights Scotch #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Nf6 4. d4
{ In order to reduce the theoretical burden, I have chosen two slightly offbeat variations in the Italian @@StartBracket@@the Scotch Gambit and the Evans Gambit@@EndBracket@@. Nevertheless, these options are definitely fair dinkum ways to obtain exciting middlegame positions for White. }
4... exd4 5. e5
{ 5.O-O  is the other main variation but this line results in more exciting positions. }
5... Ng4 { It is surprisingly difficult to gain an edge against this move. } 6.
Qe2 { Defending the e5-pawn. } 6... Bb4+ 7. c3 dxc3 8. bxc3
{ Gaining a crucial tempo on the bishop. } 8... Bc5
{ White now gains the upper hand in a shocking way. } 9. h3 Nxf2
{ If  9...Bxf2+  then  10.Kf1  and Black can't defend both the bishop and the knight. }
10. Rf1 O-O 11. Bg5
{ This is an important tempo to grab before collecting material, introducing an extra white piece into the game and forcing the black queen onto an awkward square. }
11... Qe8 12. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 13. Kxf2
{ White is clearly better. The 2 pieces for rook + 2 pawns here is heavily in favor of the two minor pieces as White’s pieces are almost entirely developed whereas the black rooks are struggling to find files and targets.   A potential follow-up can be  13...d6  14.exd6  cxd6  15.Bf4  Qd8  16.Na3  Re8  17.Qd2  and White enjoys the flawless cooperation of the minor pieces whilst  the pressure on d6 is also increasing. }
*

