5... Ng4 { It is surprisingly difficult to gain an edge against this move. } 6.
Qe2 { Defending the e5-pawn. } 6... Qe7 { Attacking our pawn once again. } 7.
Bf4 { And we defend once again. } 7... d6
{ This is Black's only way to break out of their cramped position. } 8. exd6
Qxe2+ 9. Bxe2 Bxd6 10. Bxd6
{ Naturally, White happily trades off the Bishops in order to mess up the Black pawn structure. }
10... cxd6 11. Na3 { Both c4 and b5 would be good squares for our knight. }
11... Nge5 12. Nb5
{ And this endgame is slightly better for White due to Black's double isolated d-pawns, one of which we shall regain soon. Currently, we are also threatening a fork on c7. }
