1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Nf6 4. d4
{ In order to reduce the theoretical burden, I have chosen two slightly offbeat variations in the Italian @@StartBracket@@the Scotch Gambit and the Evans Gambit@@EndBracket@@. Nevertheless, these options are definitely fair dinkum ways to obtain exciting middlegame positions for White. }
4... exd4 5. e5
{ 5.O-O  is the other main variation but this line results in more exciting positions. }
5... Ne4
{ This is the move recommended by Jan Gustaffson in his lifetime repertoire. As such, it is a very reliable variation against which we will aim to get playable, complex positions. }
6. Qe2
{ This is the most popular move at the top level, but curiously, on the 5th choice in the lichess database! }
6... Nc5 7. c3
{ The idea behind this move is to provoke Black into a gambit scenario, one that would actually be quite similar to the 2.Nf6 Sicilian Alapin variations. }
7... d3 { This is by far Black's best. } 8. Qe3
{ We have no interest in trading our bishop for the knight! } 8... Be7 9. O-O
{ Before regaining the pawn, we secure the king. This move order is slightly more accurate for White. }
9... O-O 10. b4
{ This move secures the d3-pawn without any compromise, and gains space. }
10... Ne6 11. Bxd3 d6 12. Rd1
{ White's position is most certainly easier to play. The pawn on e5 is not capturable due to the discovery with Bxh7+. White's plan is to play Bc2, to emphasize the pin along the d-file. This should be followed by Nbd2-e4 with kingside initiative. Bc2, Qe4 is also a notable motif, forcing weaknesses around the black king. }
