[White "2) Two Knights Scotch"]
[Black "Two Knights Scotch #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
{ The Italian is a trendy opening even on the very top levels and it allows us to play variations that feature both tactical skirmishes and important positional ideas. }
3... Nf6 4. d4
{ In order to reduce the theoretical burden, I have chosen two slightly offbeat variations in the Italian @@StartBracket@@the Scotch Gambit and the Evans Gambit@@EndBracket@@. Nevertheless, these options are definitely fair dinkum ways to obtain exciting middlegame positions for White. }
4... exd4 5. e5
{ 5.O-O  is the other main variation but this line results in more exciting positions. }
5... d5
{ This counterthrust is always Black's best way to respond to e5, a motif you should remember as it occurs in many other openings too! }
6. Bb5
{ Both pawn captures are bad here:  ➜  6.exd6  just develops Black's pieces after  6...Bxd6  7.O-O  O-O  and Black is ahead in development as well as on material.  The d4-pawn is immune due to  8.Nxd4??  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Bxh2+  .  ➜  6.exf6?!  dxc4  7.fxg7  Qe7+  8.Qe2  Qxe2+  9.Kxe2  Bxg7  and White has a miserable position, while Black is up a pawn, and they also have the bishop pair and the more active pieces. }
6... Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6
{ In return for the bishop pair we hope to exploit two positional factors:   ➜ The potential weakness of the dark color complex, in particular, the d4- and c5-squares;  ➜ the kingside pawn majority which is best utilized by the thematic f4-f5 plan. }
9. O-O Bc5 10. f3
{ White executes the f2-f4 idea in a seemingly delayed fashion, but in fact, playing both moves with a tempo.   The instant  10.f4  would result in the same position, but with Black to move! }
10... Ng5 11. f4 Ne4
{ The knight is now on an outpost, so one of our main strategic goals is to trade it via Nd2. }
12. Be3 Bb6 13. Nd2
{ Our best case scenario is to trade the b6-bishop and the e4-knight, thus achieving the well-known good knight vs. bad bishop situation: the blockaded c6-d5 pawns entomb the d7-bishop. }
13... c5
{ This is an ambitious plan to entirely eliminate the weak dark squares. This, however, also comes at a cost. }
14. N4f3 Nxd2 15. Qxd2 d4 16. Bf2
{ Black's accomplishments have been double-edged. The weak dark squares are gone, but now the b6-bishop is awful and Black is lacking an obvious plan to play for. }
16... Bc6 17. Bh4 Qd7 18. b3
{ A messy position with chances for both sides. White, again, aims to exploit the vulnerable light squares and create a blockade. }
