[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2.2) Two Knights Scotch - Model Games"]
[Black "G. Jones - S. Mamedyarov, World Blitz 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8.
Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 10. f3 Ng5 11. Be3 Ne6
{ This move leads to a slight deviation from our lines, but the structure and the ideas remain very similar. }
12. f4
{ Jones, one of the most notable players to regularly employ this line, immediately turns the heat up and prepares a kingside offensive with his pawn majority. }
12... Qb8 13. f5
{ This move forces the trade of the knights, but more importantly, the trade of the dark-squared bishops too. }
13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 15. Qxd4 Qb6
{ White seems to be forced to trade queens, but Jones thinks otherwise! } 16.
c3
{ A lovely move that offers Black an awkward choice: Take on b2 and allow White the domination of the dark squares, or trade on d4, once again handing over the control of vitally important squares, in particular c5. }
16... Qxd4+
{ Or  16...Qxb2  17.Nd2  O-O  18.Nb3!  with a vicious initiative for White. }
17. cxd4 Rb8 18. Nd2
{ A superb sacrifice! White correctly recognizes that the blockade on the c5-square is easily worth as much as the pawn. }
18... Rxb2 19. Nb3 Ke7 20. g4
{ White has created a mighty bind and now stands better despite the material deficit. }
20... Rb8 21. Rf2
{ A clever endgame policy: Trade your opponent's best piece! } 21... Rxf2 22.
Kxf2 g6 23. f6+ Ke8 { 23...Ke6  24.Nc5  would be a lovely checkmate pattern. }
24. Kf3 Rb4 25. Rd1 Rc4
{ Or  25...a5  26.Rd2  g5  27.Nc5  Bc8  28.h3  h6  29.Ke3  Rb1  30.Kf3  Kd8  31.Kg3  Rb4  32.Kf3  Rb1  . }
26. Rd2
{ White is missing a great opportunity here. The very thematic and natural  26.Nc5  would give White a winning edge:  26...Rb4  27.Rd3!  Rb5  28.Ra3  a5  29.Nb3  Be6  30.Rxa5  Rxa5  31.Nxa5  . }
26... Rc3+ 27. Kf4 h6 28. h4 g5+ { Black overplays his hand. } 29. hxg5 hxg5+
30. Kxg5 Rg3 31. Nc5 Rxg4+ 32. Kh5
{ Despite appearances, the black army is still very passive, largely due to the fact that the black king is under constant threat of getting mated on the back rank! }
32... Bc8 33. Rb2 Rxd4 34. Rb8 Kd8 35. e6
{ And Black is busted now. A lovely endgame by the English GM! } 35... fxe6 36.
Nxe6+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense: 3...Nxe4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move introduces the Petroff Defense, one of the most popular openings of our time. }
3. Nxe5
{ The most popular move and the most principled one. The e5-pawn is a vitally important central asset and if allowed, we should eliminate it instantly. }
3... Nxe4
{ This is a commonly played mistake here. 'Copycatting' your opponent almost always leads to disaster. }
4. Qe2 { White immediately sets about exploiting the pile-up on the e-file. }
4... Qe7 { 4...Nf6??  is disastrous as  5.Nc6+  wins the queen instantly! } 5.
Qxe4 d6
{ Black is trying to reciprocate the trickery on the e-file but theirs is far less effective. }
6. d4
{ White correctly gives up on the futile effort of saving the knight and instead focuses on rapid development. The right mentality! }
6... dxe5 7. dxe5
{ White is a pawn up, but the most important feature of the position is the unfortunate placement of the black Queen, which prevents the fluid development of the kingside... }
7... Nc6 { ... And so Black is focusing on mobilizing the queenside first. } 8.
Bb5
{ White develops the bishop, and defends the e5-pawn indirectly with help of the pin. }
8... Bd7 { Renewing the threat on e5 and preparing to castle. } 9. Nc3
{ White cleverly ignores the threat and continues developing. Remember: Dynamic considerations almost always outweigh material ones! }
9... O-O-O
{ 9...Qxe5??  loses a piece to  10.Bxc6  Qxe4+  11.Bxe4  with a winning advantage for White.   9...Nxe5  is also really bad due to  10.Nd5  Qd6  11.Bf4  f6  12.Bxe5  fxe5  13.Bxd7+  and Black is utterly lost. }
10. Bf4 { The most logical way to develop and keep the pawn guarded. } 10... g5
11. Bg3 Bg7 12. O-O-O
{ Just like before, we rely on piece activity and tactical threats, rather than passively defending the pawn. It turns out that Black has no good way to recover the lost material. }
12... Nxe5 13. Bxd7+ Rxd7 14. Rxd7
{ Black has to take with the king due to the hanging e5-knight. } 14... Kxd7
15. Qxb7 { And the exposed black king will not last much longer... } *

