{ The most popular move and the most principled one. The e5-pawn is a vitally important central asset and if allowed, we should eliminate it instantly. }
3... Nc6
{ Introducing the very popular but perfectly unsound Stafford Gambit. Due to some popular content creators' work, this line has become one of the most popular gambits at the club level and so we need to be very well prepared. }
4. Nxc6
{ White's best move is to accept the pawn and with it the challenge as well! }
4... dxc6
{ With this recapture, Black forgoes all hopes of central control with pawns, as their e-pawn was sacrificed and the d-pawn took back on c6. Instead, Black's hopes are exclusively based on tactical tricks. }
5. d3
{ The safest way to play. Amazingly, the utterly ugly  5.f3  is also good @@StartBracket@@I even promoted that move in a video of mine@@EndBracket@@ but the text is just easier to play and looks optically more sound too. }
5... Bc5
{ Black develops the bishop and prepares a range of traps. White needs to be very cautious here! }
6. Be2
{ Not only is this a vital developing move but also a crucial defensive measure: the g4-square needed to be covered! }
6... h5 7. c3
{ This somewhat ugly move is perfectly fine here as Black also played a non-developing move  @@StartBracket@@h7-h5@@EndBracket@@. White is aiming to build a massive center with d3-d4, virtually shutting out the Black minor pieces. }
7... Be6 8. d4
{ MIssion complete! White's domination of the middle is too much for Black to handle. }
8... Be7 { 8...Bd6?  loses a piece to  9.e5  . } 9. Nd2
{ Time to complete development! } 9... Qd7 10. Qc2
{ Reinforcing e4 and thus allowing for the final phase of White's mobilisation. }
10... O-O-O 11. Nf3
{ White is dominating the game with a large center and an extra pawn. Apart from the calm Bg5 followed by O-O, White also has a promising attack after a4-b4-b5! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense: 3...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move introduces the Petroff Defense, one of the most popular openings of our time. }
3. Nxe5
{ The most popular move and the most principled one. The e5-pawn is a vitally important central asset and if allowed, we should eliminate it instantly. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { White's best retreat. } 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the second most popular move in this position after the main move  5.d4  . White aims to trade off the e4-knight and accelerate the development of the c1-bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. d4
{ Since Black's d6-d5 is more or less forced, White is two tempi up in a symmetrical structure. Although Black has a very real chance to equalize, Grand Master practice shows that White has plenty to play for! }
6... Be7
{ Black is preparing to castle, but now the bishop on e7 is a touch too passive. }
7. Bd3
{ White, in turn, develops the bishop more aggressively, taking aim at the central e4-square and the potential target on h7. }
7... Bg4 { This is poking the bear a touch too hard! } 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4
{ A move that a lot of club-level players are extremely reluctant to make, because they fear that it will weaken the kingside. The truth is, however, that it strengthens the kingside @@StartBracket@@with the aim of attacking there@@EndBracket@@ and our king will happily castle the other way. Don't be afraid of ghosts! }
9... Bg6 10. g5
{ White keeps on delaying their own development in order to hassle the already developed black pieces. White is getting ahead not by improving their position but more so by making Black's position gradually worse! }
10... Nfd7 11. Be3
{ White is much better due to the better development and promising attacking chances on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense: 3...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move introduces the Petroff Defense, one of the most popular openings of our time. }
3. Nxe5
{ The most popular move and the most principled one. The e5-pawn is a vitally important central asset and if allowed, we should eliminate it instantly. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { White's best retreat. } 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the second most popular move in this position after the main move  5.d4  . White aims to trade off the e4-knight and accelerate the development of the c1-bishop. }
5... Nf6 6. d4
{ Since Black's d6-d5 is more or less forced, White is two tempi up in a symmetrical structure. Although Black has a very real chance to equalize, Grand Master practice shows that White has plenty to play for! }
6... Be7
{ Black is preparing to castle, but now the bishop on e7 is a touch too passive. }
7. Bd3
{ White, in turn, develops the bishop more aggressively, taking aim at the central e4-square and the potential target on h7. }
7... O-O 8. O-O Bg4 9. h3
{ Even if White does not plan to expand with g2-g4 @@StartBracket@@which, by the way, is by no means ruled out by the fact that we castled kingside!@@EndBracket@@, this poking move is always worth inserting, as now the bishop has to decide which diagonal to stay on and which one to give up. }
9... Bh5 10. Re1
{ White is still not committing to developing the c1-bishop as its best square is yet to be found. }
10... Re8 11. g4
{ White is more than OK with a kingside expansion as our 'weak' king is merely an academic fact that can't be exploited in reality. On the other hand, the black pieces are again treading on each other's toes. }
11... Bg6 12. g5 Nh5 13. Bf1
{ This re-routing idea secures a sizeable advantage to White. We are planning to relocate the bishop to g2 where it would protect the king very well whilst controlling the long diagonal. The main advantage lies in the fact that the knight on h5 is utterly out of the game and could even become a target. }
