[White "3) Petroff Defense"]
[Black "Petroff Defense: 3...d6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ This move introduces the Petroff Defense, one of the most popular openings of our time. }
3. Nxe5
{ The most popular move and the most principled one. The e5-pawn is a vitally important central asset and if allowed, we should eliminate it instantly. }
3... d6 4. Nf3 { White's best retreat. } 4... Nxe4 5. Nc3
{ This is the second most popular move in this position after the main move  5.d4  . White aims to trade off the e4-knight and accelerate the development of the c1-bishop. }
5... Nxc3 { Black's most thematic move. } 6. dxc3
{ The right recapture, as it opens up the diagonal of the Bishop and offers White a semi-open file to play along. }
6... Be7
{ By far the most popular move, although it has to be stated that many other move orders are possible here. Most likely, they will transpose to our main line.  For example, at this point,  6...Nc6  first, followed by Be7, is also commonplace. }
7. Be3
{ White's main goal in this system is to quickly castle queenside and launch an attack depending on what direction the Black king chooses to go. }
7... Nc6
{ 7...d5  is too early here as White can now chip away at the central pawn easily with  8.c4!  , immediately seeking confrontation in the center. That's the right way to play! }
8. Qd2
{ White consistently carries out the intention to tuck away the king on the queenside. }
8... Be6
{ The bishop is annoyingly aiming at a2, making castling a touch more problematic. }
9. O-O-O { Anyway! It turns out that the a2-pawn is poisoned! } 9... Qd7
{ Black floats the possibility of castling either side, thus making White's choice a bit trickier. }
10. Kb1
{ Simply securing the a2-pawn and stepping out of checks on the h6-c1 diagonal. }
10... Bf6 11. h4
{ This is a typical method we use to begin a kingside attack. This move is useful even if the black king chooses to castle the other way, as it gains space and provides a springboard on g5 for the white minor pieces. }
11... O-O-O 12. Nd4
{ This is an important move to remember! White is playing chess where we are meant to: in da Centah! The knight jump prepares the trade of important black defenders, in particular the c6-knight. }
12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4
{ And White has the upper hand as now  13...Bxd4  is simply losing to  14.Qxd4  with a double  attack on the a7- and g7-pawns. }
