[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2) Petroff Defense - Model Games"]
[Black "S. Fedorchuk - Ni Hua, World Blitz 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. d4 Be7 7. Bd3 O-O 8.
O-O Nc6 9. a3 Bg4
{ With the exception of a3 and Nc6, we are following our Petroff line. The upcoming aggression by Fedorchuk demonstrates the right mentality for these positions. }
10. h3 Bh5
{ 10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3  Nxd4  12.Qxb7  is just awful for Black: White has the two bishops and Black's structure has been damaged. }
11. g4
{ Both our Petroff and Scandinavian lines feature this bold pawn push. It is important to understand that the black king is much more likely to become a target of an attack than his white colleague, despite the initial impressions... }
11... Bg6 12. Bxg6 hxg6 13. d5
{ Kicking the developed knight... True, it will jump to the center, but e5 is not a secure outpost! }
13... Ne5 14. Nd4 Re8 15. f4
{ Fedorchuk's chess shows no compromise, the vicious aggression is about to yield noticeable results. }
15... Nc4 16. Qd3 Nb6 17. f5
{ Inspired play! Having chased the c6-knight all the way to b6, Fedorchuk now switches back to the kingside to continue what he began: A relentless and uncompromising kingside attack. }
17... gxf5 18. Nxf5 c6 19. Bg5
{ Unfortunately, the tight time control did not allow Fedorchuk to find a deep but lovely winning idea:  19.g5?!  Nfxd5  20.Qg3!  and Black has no meaningful defense against the dual threats of g5-g6 and Nh6+! A possible variation would be  20...Bf8  21.g6  Nf6  22.Bh6!!  gxh6  23.g7  Nh5  24.Nxh6+  Kh7  25.g8=Q+  Kxh6  26.Qh8  . }
19... Nbxd5 20. Nxe7+
{ Regrettably, Fedorchuk drops the ball for the second time. A sensational finish was up for grabs, crowning his masterful opening and early midgame play:  20.Nxd5!  Nxd5  21.Nh6+!!  gxh6  22.Rxf7!!  when the reward for the uncompromising attack is a stunning sacrificial finish, worthy of a beauty prize! Checkmate is inevitable:  22...Kxf7  23.Qh7+  Ke6  24.Qf5  . }
20... Qxe7 21. Nxd5 cxd5 22. Bxf6 gxf6
{ After the unnecessary trades, Fedorchuk ends up in a marginally better endgame, which he converted into a long struggle. }
23. Rf2 Qe5 24. c3 Re6 25. Raf1 Rae8 26. Rf5 Qe2 27. Qxe2 Rxe2 28. R1f2 R8e5
29. Rxf6 R2e3 30. Kg2 Re7 31. Rxd6 Rd3 32. Rdf6 Kg7 33. R6f3 Rd1 34. Rf5 Rd3
35. Rg5+ Kf8 36. Rh5 Ke8 37. Rh8+ Kd7 38. Rf8 Ke6 39. h4 Re3 40. h5 Re4 41. Kg3
Re3+ 42. Kh4 Re1 43. Kg5 Re5+ 44. Rf5 Re2 45. Rf6+ Ke5 46. R8xf7 Re8 47. Rf8
Re7 48. R6f7 Re6 49. h6 Rh2 50. Rf6 Re7 51. R8f7 Re8 52. Rf5+ Ke4 53. h7 Rh8
54. Kg6 Rxb2 55. Rf8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3.2) Petroff Defense - Model Games"]
[Black "V. Anand - R. Kasimdzhanov, Tashkent 2011"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nxe5 d6 4. Nf3 Nxe4 5. Nc3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Be7 7. Be3 Nc6
8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O Ne5 10. Kb1
{ It is important to note here that  10...Nxf3  11.gxf3  does not bother us at all, in fact, we would warmly welcome the opening of the g-file against the black king @@StartBracket@@out of more than 400, not a single master game followed that path@@EndBracket@@! }
10... c6 11. Be2 Ng4 12. Bd3
{ Anand re-routes the bishop to the good d3-square as it is no longer monitored by the knight. }
12... d5
{ 12...Nxe3  13.Qxe3  Bf6  14.h4  is the type of position we play this system for. White certainly has more going on the kingside! }
13. Bf4
{ Having been given the opportunity, Anand now wisely opts to get the best of both worlds by retaining the bishop pair and plans to kick the knight with h3. }
13... Bd6 14. h3 Bxf4
{ This careless move brings about a tactical skirmish, in which Anand is in a class of his own. }
15. Bxh7+ { A brilliant intermezzo, which rips the black defenses apart! }
15... Kh8 { Or  15...Kxh7  16.hxg4+  Bh6  17.g5  with a decisive attack. } 16.
Qxf4 Nxf2
{ Kasidhzanov hopes to gobble up some material in return for his exposed king. }
17. Ng5
{ This obvious-looking move seems to walk into the equally obvious response f6. Anand, however, calculated further. }
17... f6 18. Nf7+ { A fantastic strike! } 18... Rxf7 19. Bg6
{ And now Black is facing multiple threats, the most pressing among them being the queen's invasion via the h-file! }
19... Nxd1
{ Kasimdzhanov crumbles under the pressure. The engine's preferred line looks rather unattractive too:  19...f5  20.Qxf2±  and White has restored the material parity and retained all his attacking trumps. However, the game is still to be won! }
20. Qh4+ Kg8 21. Re1
{ A sensational finish to an amazing attacking game. Black can't avoid checkmate anymore without heavy material losses. }
21... Nxc3+ 22. bxc3 Be6 23. Rxe6 Qb6+ 24. Kc1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Philidor Defense"]
[Black "Philidor Defense: 3...Bg4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ This is the Philidor Defense, named after the outstanding French chess player and music composer from the 1700s @@StartBracket@@also known by the name Francios Danican Philidor@@EndBracket@@. Although this defense is rather passive, due to the limited scope of the f8-bishop it should not be underestimated! }
3. d4
{ This move has been known ever since the 'Opera game' - most likely the most famous chess game ever played! White immediately challenges the center and seeks confrontation. }
3... Bg4
{ This was also played in the famous opera game. Black is hoping to tie White down with this pin, but it simply does not work, as we will see. }
4. dxe5
{ This move forces Black to either trade on f3 or enter a dodgy gambit. } 4...
Nc6
{ This is a trendy line these days but it has very little venom if White plays natural moves.  The opera game went  4...Bxf3  5.Qxf3  dxe5  6.Bc4  Nf6  7.Qb3  Qe7  8.Nc3  c6  9.Bg5  .    4...dxe5  simply loses on the spot:  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Nxe5  . }
5. exd6
{ As so often, the best way to refute a dodgy gambit is to simply accept it! }
5... Bxd6 6. Nc3 { White calmly develops and keeps a sizeable edge. } 6... Nf6
7. h3 Bh5 8. Bb5 { White develops and restricts at the same time! } 8... Qe7 9.
Bg5
{ White utilizes the freedom of the minor pieces. Black is clearly lacking sufficient play for the sacrificed pawn. }
9... Bb4 10. Bxf6
{ This simplification allows us to eliminate any hope of play. } 10... Qxf6 11.
Qd4
{ And with the prospect of an endgame with an extra pawn, White is way ahead. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Philidor Defense"]
[Black "Philidor Defense: 3...exd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6
{ This is the Philidor Defense, named after the outstanding French chess player and music composer from the 1700s @@StartBracket@@also known by the name Francios Danican Philidor@@EndBracket@@. Although this defense is rather passive, due to the limited scope of the f8-bishop it should not be underestimated! }
3. d4
{ This move has been known ever since the 'Opera game' - most likely the most famous chess game ever played! White immediately challenges the center and seeks confrontation. }
3... exd4
{ This moves surrenders the center and releases the tension but Black has some play against the e4-pawn. }
4. Nxd4
{ 4.Qxd4  is also playable here but the knight recapture is more thematic. }
4... Nf6 { Black immediately begins developing while also hitting the center. }
5. Nc3
{ In most openings, this natural developing move is the best way to protect the central e4-pawn. }
5... Be7
{ Black correctly prioritizes the development of their kingside, which allows them quick castling and a new attacking piece @@StartBracket@@the rook@@EndBracket@@ against the e4-pawn. }
6. Be2
{ This humble move allows White an extra defender of the e4-pawn, which, as we shall see soon, is rather needed! }
6... O-O { Simple and logical. } 7. O-O
{ Since White is uncertain about the optimal square for the c1-bishop, it makes sense to develop everything else first! }
7... Re8
{ Black begins an operation that is very typical in many openings in which Black tries to pressure the e4-pawn @@StartBracket@@King's Indian Defense is a good example@@EndBracket@@. }
8. f4
{ A very important move. White is preparing to back up the center with Bf3, but before doing so, we claim a large chunk of the center! }
8... Bf8 { Black continues to carry out their plan logically. } 9. Bf3
{ f3 is a very good square for the bishop. It covers the pawn on e4 and also monitors the g4-square so that the black minor pieces can't use it as a springboard. }
9... Nc6 10. Be3
{ A very pleasant position for White, as Black has no meaningful way to contest the white center. }
*

