3. d4
{ This move has been known ever since the 'Opera game' - most likely the most famous chess game ever played! White immediately challenges the center and seeks confrontation. }
3... Nd7
{ This move is the main variation of the Philidor Defense, although the capture on d4 is also a popular choice. Black opts to defend the e5-pawn without allowing their knight to be pestered.   3...Nf6  transposes into the main line after the moves:  4.Nc3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  O-O  7.Re1  c6  8.a4  . }
4. Bc4
{ This thematic developing move is very akin to the Italian @@StartBracket@@Giuoco Piano@@EndBracket@@ setups. White is aiming to cause discomfort around the weak f7-pawn. }
4... c6
{ Black's most common response in this position. The key idea is to take control over the d5-square. We already saw in the 4...Be7 line how important this can be. }
5. Nc3
{ Although  5.O-O  has a marginally better reputation, we should stick to this move as the variation most often occurs via the 'Pirc' move order, when the white knight is already committed to the c3-square. }
5... Be7
{ Black has to develop the bishop first in order to prevent the Ng5-threat. }
6. O-O
{ White completes the development of their kingside and secures the king. }
6... Ngf6
{ Black completes their kingside development as well. Although the black position may look passive, the flexible pawn formation on the queenside needs some kind of preventative measure from White. }
7. a4
{ This is it! A move whose importance is often overlooked. White drastically restricts Black's chances for a queenside expansion. Executing the desired b7-b5 break will take serious preparation by Black now. }
7... O-O { Black's kingside is fully developed albeit somewhat passively. } 8.
Re1 { White reinforces the e4-pawn and brings another piece into the battle. }
8... b6
{ Black opts to develop the bishop to b7, and also hopes to play for a b6-b5 break after preparing it with a6. }
9. h3
{ White plays a useful move and prepares for a kingside initiative once the black bishop is no longer covering f5. In the same spirit,  9.Ba2  was also recommendable.   Note that we usually very strongly disapprove of the 'bunny ears' h3- and a3-pawn moves, but here White actually benefits from delaying the development of the c1-bishop. }
9... Bb7 10. dxe5
{ Another move that breaks a number of super important principles, but it is actually a necessary preparation for a successful kingside offensive.  The plan is  10.Nh4  but without the introductory capture on e5, it just does not work:  10...exd4  11.Qxd4  d5!  and Black's counterpunch in the center comes perfectly well-timed, as the scattered white pieces are not ready for the battle. }
10... dxe5 11. Nh4
{ A very common maneuver in a number of e4-e5 openings. The idea is rerouting the knight to the f5-square, from where it exerts enormous pressure on the black kingside. @@StartBracket@@I talk about the f5-knight in great detail in my 'CPR King Safety' course as one of the most potent attackers against a short castled king!@@EndBracket@@ }
11... Nc5 12. Nf5
{ White has successfully landed the knight on the desired outpost. White's pieces are better placed and our kingside initiative is gaining momentum.  12...Qxd1  is now met by  13.Nxe7+  winning on the spot. The best way to continue our kingside aggression  is to play Qf3-g3 and then Bg5 or Bh6 even, depending on how Black reacts. }
