[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2) Philidor Defense - Model Games"]
[Black "A. Neiksans - V. Kiselev, Petrov Memorial Rapid 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Re8 8.
f4 Bf8 9. Bf3 c5 10. Nde2 { 10.Nb3  is also a popular move in this position. }
10... Nc6 11. h3
{ This move takes the sting out of potential jumps to g4 and also hints at the idea of a g2-g4-g5 attack. }
11... h5
{ Black over-reacts and in doing so, he makes his kingside vulnerable to attacks. }
12. f5
{ Neiksans immediately pulls the trigger! This pawn thrust is a hugely commital move as it surrenders the central e5-square forever, but it also secures d5 for the white cavalry. Additionally, both black bishops are struggling to find a good diagonal. }
12... Ne5 13. Nf4 b5
{ Black is trying to generate counterplay, but this move just forces White to do what he wanted to do anyway: to conquer the d5-square. }
14. Nxh5
{ Not only does this move net a pawn but it also eliminates the defender of the d5-square.   14.Nxb5?  is wrong both tactically and strategically: we lose control of the d5-square and Black can generate strong play against the e4-pawn with  14...Bb7  . }
14... Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Nxh5 16. Qxh5 b4 17. Nd5
{ The dust has settled. White has emerged with an extra pawn and, more importantly, a fantastic attacking position on the kingside. }
17... Rxe4 18. Bg5 f6 19. Rae1
{ The position was ripe for violence! Here, Neiksans missed the lovely:  19.Qg6!!  Be7  @@StartBracket@@or  19...fxg5  20.f6!  and checkmate is imminent@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@r1bq2k1/p3b1p1/3p1pQ1/2pN1PB1/1p2r3/7P/PPP3P1/R4RK1 w - - 2 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Bh6  Qf8  21.Rae1  Re5  22.Rxe5  dxe5  23.Rf3!  and White's relentless attack breaks through. }
19... Bb7 20. Bxf6
{ The mundane  20.Rxe4  would have been far cleaner:  20...Bxd5  21.Rh4  fxg5  22.f6!!  gxh4  23.Qxd5+  Kh7  24.Qh5+  Kg8  25.f7  with a gorgeous checkmate. }
20... gxf6 21. Rxe4 Bxd5 22. Rg4+ Bg7 23. Re1
{ White now has to do some extra lifting to secure the win. } 23... Qd7 24. Re3
Rf8 25. Kh2 Rf7 26. Rxg7+ { A lovely finale! } 26... Kxg7 27. Rg3+ Kf8 28. Qh8+
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.2) Philidor Defense - Model Games"]
[Black "V. Potkin - V. Bologan, World Rapid Championship 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d6 2. e4 Nf6 3. Nc3 e5 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bc4 Be7 6. O-O O-O 7. Re1 c6 8. a4
b6 9. d5
{ This move introduces a positional plan based on the idea of exploiting the d5 outpost. }
9... Bb7 10. dxc6 Bxc6
{ White's goal now is very simple: He aims to trade down all the black pieces that can control the d5-square, so that he can place an unopposed knight @@StartBracket@@or a bishop in some cases@@EndBracket@@ there. }
11. Bg5 a6 12. Bxf6
{ Although this move violates the principle of favoring bishops over knights, in this case, it is justified by the plan to conquer the d5-square! }
12... Nxf6 13. Qd3 Qc8 14. Nd2
{ This move introduces another typical maneuver in this structure: The knight is taking a long journey towards d5. }
14... Qb7 { Black is taking aim at e4, thus denying the plan of Nf1-e3. } 15.
b4
{ White takes aim at the bishop on c6, which is not only an attacker of the e4-pawn but more importantly a vital defender of the d5-square. }
15... Qc8
{ 15...b5  would have been a clever attempt by Black to change the nature of the game from a positional squeeze to a tactical skirmish! After  16.axb5  axb5  17.Rxa8  Rxa8  18.Bxb5  Bxb5  19.Nxb5  d5  White still has his work cut out for him. }
16. Nf1 a5 17. b5 Bd7 18. Ne3 Qc5 19. Ncd5
{ And White's strategic goal has been accomplished! The next stage is to find a weakness @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ to target. To begin with, b6 is very vulnerable. }
19... Nxd5 20. Nxd5 Bd8 21. Bb3 Kh8 22. Qe3
{ Positional superiority is often best exploited in endgame scenarios and so White gladly invites a queen trade. }
22... Rc8 23. Rad1 Be6 24. Rd3
{ White gradually builds up his position. Patience @@StartBracket@@in this case, optimizing piece placement@@EndBracket@@ is indeed a virtue! }
24... Bxd5 25. Rxd5 Qxe3 26. Rxe3
{ Although White's position is undeniably better, there is still a lot of work to be done. We need to maximize the activity of our pieces and find targets! }
26... Be7 27. g3 g6 28. Kg2 Kg7 29. f4
{ White needs either semi-open or open files to make his rooks more effective. This means trading a few pawns. }
29... f6 30. Red3 Rfd8 31. Kf3 Rc5 32. h4 Rxd5 33. Bxd5 Rc8 34. c4
{ This move shuts down all hopes of counterplay. White can now focus all his efforts on the kingside. }
34... Rf8 35. f5
{ This lovely move is a particularly venomous one as it invites the positional blunder  35...gxf5  36.exf5  h5  37.Ke4!  and White has an additional plan now: infiltration with the king on the white squares. }
35... g5 36. hxg5 fxg5 37. Kg4
{ Although it may look like White is putting all his eggs in one basket by playing for a kingside break, the position has a hidden resource on the other wing: the c4-c5 break! }
37... h5+
{ Black happily sacrifices a pawn for piece activity - a trademark of a good endgame player! }
38. Kxh5 Rh8+ 39. Kg4 Kf6 40. Be6 Rh1 41. c5
{ Just when things started to look up for Black, White delivers him a rude shock! }
41... dxc5
{ 41...bxc5  42.Rb3  is terminal. Note the stark difference between the two bishops. }
42. Rd7 Re1 43. Bd5
{ Black is completely dominated by the active white pieces. The black bishop is glued to e7 in order to shield the mate on f7, so White can freely grab the b6-pawn. }
43... c4 44. Rc7 c3
{ The only way to prevent the disaster on b6, but this just loses too much. The rest requires no commentary. }
45. Rc6+ Kg7 46. Rxc3 Bc5 47. Kxg5 Be3+ 48. Kg4 Bc5 49. Rc2 Rh1 50. Kg5 Be3+
51. Kg4 Bc5 52. Rxc5 bxc5 53. Kg5 Rc1 54. f6+ Kf8 55. b6 Rb1 56. b7 c4 57. Bxc4
Rxb7 58. Kf5 Rb4 59. Bb5 Rb3 60. g4 Rf3+ 61. Kxe5 Kf7 62. Bc4+ Kg6 63. f7 Kg7
64. g5 Ra3 65. Kd6 Kf8 66. g6 Rg3 67. e5 Rxg6+ 68. e6 Rf6 69. Kd7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Damiano Defense, Elephant Gambit and Latvian Gambit"]
[Black "Damiano Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f6
{ This is the Damiano Defense. An opening that is unjustly named on account of its weaknesses, notwithstanding Damiano's excellent chess skills. There is a well-known theory that Damiano's name was given to this terrible move by his greatest rivals in order to blemish his legacy! }
3. Nxe5
{ A very rare case when an opening blunder can be punished as early as move 3 by a spectacular sacrifice! }
3... Qe7 { This is the lesser evil, but even here, Black is in bad shape. } 4.
Nf3 Qxe4+ 5. Be2
{ White is aiming to castle as quickly as possible so as to exploit the awkward line-up of the black heavy pieces. }
5... Ne7 6. O-O
{ White has an abundance of great moves including  6.Nc3  ,  6.d4  , etc. }
6... d5 7. Re1
{ White is simultaneously developing the pieces and creating deadly threats. }
7... Bd7
{ A sad necessity. Black had to deal with the discovered attack with Bb5+. } 8.
d4 { White grabs the center and prepares the development of the queenside. }
8... Nbc6 9. Nc3
{ Nothing like developing with a tempo! Black has spent too many moves maneuvering the wayward queen and punishment is imminent. }
9... Qg6 10. Ne5
{ The killer blow! When Black is just about to stabilize and castle out of trouble, this hammer blow decides the game instantly. The queen is trapped! }
10... fxe5 { 10...Qf5  is no improvement on account of  11.Bg4  . } 11. Bh5
{ Pinning and winning the Royalty. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Damiano Defense, Elephant Gambit and Latvian Gambit"]
[Black "Damiano Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f6
{ This is the Damiano Defense. An opening that is unjustly named on account of its weaknesses, notwithstanding Damiano's excellent chess skills. There is a well-known theory that Damiano's name was given to this terrible move by his greatest rivals in order to blemish his legacy! }
3. Nxe5
{ A very rare case when an opening blunder can be punished as early as move 3 by a spectacular sacrifice! }
3... fxe5 4. Qh5+
{ This early queen sortie is fully justified here as Black has no adequate defense against the relentless checks. }
4... g6 { This is even worse than  4...Ke7  which we'll see here. } 5. Qxe5+
{ The double attack decides the game instantly. } 5... Kf7
{ If  5...Qe7  then simply  6.Qxh8  but the text move makes matters even worse. }
6. Bc4+ d5 7. Bxd5+ Be6 8. Qxe6+
{ The correct capture, after which the black king gets mated in a few moves. }
8... Kg7 9. Qf7+
{ White begins the final assault. The king is not long for this world. } 9...
Kh6 10. d4+ { A nice discovered check that introduces another attacker. } 10...
g5 11. h4 { And mate is inevitable! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Damiano Defense, Elephant Gambit and Latvian Gambit"]
[Black "Damiano Defense #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f6
{ This is the Damiano Defense. An opening that is unjustly named on account of its weaknesses, notwithstanding Damiano's excellent chess skills. There is a well-known theory that Damiano's name was given to this terrible move by his greatest rivals in order to blemish his legacy! }
3. Nxe5
{ A very rare case when an opening blunder can be punished as early as move 3 by a spectacular sacrifice! }
3... fxe5 4. Qh5+
{ This early queen sortie is fully justified here as Black has no adequate defense against the relentless checks. }
4... Ke7 5. Qxe5+
{ The attack plays itself, as the black king is exposed to a range of checks every step of the way. }
5... Kf7 6. Bc4+
{ White strikes the iron while it's hot. Developing with checks is always a plus! }
6... d5
{ A necessary intermezzo by Black in order to cover the f5-square.  If  6...Kg6  then  7.Qf5+  Kh6  8.d4+  g5  9.h4  and White forces mate in a few more moves, e.g.  9...Be7  10.hxg5+  Kg7  11.Qf7#  . }
7. Bxd5+ { White continues the chase. } 7... Kg6 8. h4
{ An excellent attacking move, hinting at h4-h5 check with dire consequences. }
8... h6
{ Black is trying to escape via h7, a clever defensive operation that is met by a cunning retort: }
9. Bxb7
{ A most unexpected strike on the other end of the board. It turns out that the bishop is immune! }
9... Bxb7 10. Qf5# { The point of the decoy sacrifice. Black is mated. } *

