1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ This is the so-called Elephant Gambit, but do not be fooled! Unlike its namesake, the opening is neither sturdy nor long-lived.  Such early impulsive moves are usually soundly punished and this is no exception! }
3. exd5
{ This is the correct capture. White is tempting Black to bring their queen out too early. }
3... Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5 5. Bc4
{ As is often the case in e4-e5 openings, White takes aim at the weak f7-pawn. }
5... Nc6 6. O-O Be6 { Black needs to neutralize the powerful c4-bishop. } 7.
Bxe6
{ White happily accepts the trade in exchange for Black's horrific pawn structure. }
7... fxe6 8. d3
{ And White has a big advantage. The double isolated e-pawns are always going to be easy targets. Aside from the weak pawns, White often ends up developing a nice attack on the queenside.   E.g.  8...Nf6  9.Bd2  ,  this move makes the queen on a5 feel uncomfortable.  9...O-O-O  10.a3  @@StartBracket@@plan b2-b4@@EndBracket@@  10...Nd4  11.b4  Nxf3+  12.Qxf3  Qb6  13.Be3  with a strong queenside attack. }
*

