1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5
{ This is the so-called Elephant Gambit, but do not be fooled! Unlike its namesake, the opening is neither sturdy nor long-lived.  Such early impulsive moves are usually soundly punished and this is no exception! }
3. exd5
{ This is the correct capture. White is tempting Black to bring their queen out too early. }
3... e4 4. Qe2
{ Although this move obstructs the development of the white kingside, it also causes discomfort in Black's camp. The e4-pawn has advanced too far from the rest of the black army and is now an easy target. }
4... Nf6
{ Black's idea is to rapidly develop the kingside and create threats along the e-file. }
5. d3 { White continues attacking the vulnerable black central pawn. } 5...
Qxd5 6. Nbd2
{ Although  6.Nc3  might look more appealing, the text is more accurate as it denies Black the  6...Bb4  option. }
6... Bf5 { Insisting on keeping the e4-pawn leads to instant collapse: } 7.
dxe4 Nxe4 8. Ng5 { Black loses a piece and with it the game! } *

