[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Damiano Defense, Elephant Gambit and Latvian Gambit"]
[Black "Latvian Gambit #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5
{ Black attempts to play a 'reversed King's Gambit'. As is usually the case with early gambits on the black side, this one is rather easily refuted. }
3. Nxe5
{ The correct way to capture.  3.exf5  e4  is rather messy, exactly what Black is after. }
3... Qf6
{ A repeated pattern: an early queen move once again. And again, Black will have to pay the price. The reason why this move is the main choice here for Black is simple: most other moves allow the deadly Qh5+, e.g.  3...d6  4.Qh5+  g6  5.Nxg6  Nf6  6.Qh4  . }
4. d4
{ As always, play in the center @@StartBracket@@Centah!@@EndBracket@@ whenever possible! This move also opens the diagonal for the c1-bishop. }
4... d6
{ 4...fxe4  is inaccurate here due to  5.Bc4!  and Black is helpless against the incoming Nf7. }
5. Nc4 { The best square for the knight under the circumstances. } 5... fxe4 6.
Nc3
{ White is already ahead in development and our pieces are coming out with tempi. }
6... Qg6 { Another queen move is necessary to keep the e4-pawn guarded. } 7. f3
{ Although this is only the second choice of the silicone monster, I find it to be far easier to justify. White is aiming to eliminate Black's only trump card - the e4-pawn- and also liberate our own position. This allows further tempo developing moves such as Bd3. }
7... Nf6 8. fxe4 Nxe4 9. Bd3 { Attacking and pinning the knight. } 9... Bf5 10.
Qf3 { The black position is busted. } *

