[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5.2)  Elephant Gambit and Latvian Gambit - Model Games"]
[Black "V. Ivanchuk - A. Gadimbayli, European Online Championship 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 d5 3. exd5 e4 4. Qe2 Nf6 5. d3 Bb4+
{ Black deviates from our main line, which goes  5...Qxd5  . The young Azeri GM tries to steer the game towards a wild tactical skirmish, but this hardly makes up for his unsound opening play. }
6. c3 { Scoring a free tempo on the bishop. } 6... O-O
{ In true coffee-house style, Black attempts to create chaos at all costs. This is very typical at club chess as well. In such cases, the best policy is to remain calm and not believe your opponent's bluff. }
7. dxe4
{ Of course, Ivanchuk is not interested in exposing his king after:  7.cxb4?  exf3  8.Qxf3  Re8+  with serious counter-chances. }
7... Bd6 8. Bg5
{ Even on the very top level, chess principles remain the same: 'weird stuff gets beaten by regular stuff'! In this spirit, Ivanchuk simply continues development. }
8... Re8 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. g3
{ This slightly odd move, straight from Planet Ivanchuk, is one of the many good ways to maintain the advantage.   10.O-O-O  was another valid way to go. }
10... h6 11. Bxf6
{ Here, Ivanchuk opts to follow a principle known since Steinitz: When ahead in material, it is often wise to return some of it in order to consolidate your position. }
11... Nxf6 12. Bg2 Nxd5 13. O-O
{ The tactical sequence is over, it is time to take stock: White has completed development and retained an extra pawn. The rest should be easy, but it is always wise to see how elite GMs convert these advantages. }
13... Nf6 14. e5
{ Ivanchuk retains the pressure. Maintaining an aggressive mindset is vital to prevent our opponent from seizing the initiative. Although the pawn thrust does not create an instant threat because it is pinned, it certainly does cause discomfort. }
14... Ng4 { Or  14...Bg4  15.Qb5!  . } 15. Nc4 f6 16. Rad1
{ Excellent play by the Ukrainian Super GM. He is more than happy to return even a second pawn in order to accomplish total domination! }
16... fxe5
{ 16...Nxe5  superbly demonstrates the above mentioned domination:  17.Nfxe5  fxe5  18.Nxd6  cxd6  19.Rd2  Qf6  20.Rfd1  Rd8  21.c4  and now White holds all the positional trump cards. Black is virtually paralysed. }
17. h3 Nf6 18. Nfxe5 Qe7 19. Rfe1
{ White dominates every part of the board and is still up material! } 19...
Bxe5 20. Nxe5 c6 21. Rd3
{ Allowing White to either double on the d-file, or triple on the e-file. }
21... Bf5 22. Re3 Qc7 23. g4 Be6
{ Black crumbles under the pressure, but he could hardly do anything else. }
24. Nxc6 { Ivanchuk mops up the rest with ease. } 24... Bxa2 25. Ne7+ Kf8 26.
Qb5 Bf7 27. Qb4 Qc4 28. Ng6+ Kg8 29. Rxe8+ Rxe8 30. Rxe8+ Nxe8 31. Qf8+ Kh7 32.
Ne5 *

