[Black "P. Kotsur - B. Asanov, Kurgan 1993"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is a great example of how quickly Black can collapse when playing unsound openings. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 f5 3. Nxe5 Qf6 4. d4 d6 5. Nc4 fxe4 6. Nc3 Bf5
{ Amazingly, barring one move, White is going to play the rest of the game with his knights only! }
7. Ne3 Bg6 8. Ned5 Qf7 9. Nf4
{ This knight maneuver allows White to grab the bishop any time and also prepares an invasion on e6. }
9... Nf6 10. d5 { Now Black has no way to stop the invasion on e6. } 10... Nbd7
11. Ne6
{ 11.Nb5  would have been even more accurate, according to Stockfish, but engines are known to have no appreciation for aesthetics! }
11... Ne5 12. Nb5
{ Black has had enough, the white cavalry has done too much damage already! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... e5
{ This move is actually nowhere near as bad as it looks!   Note that  2...e6  does not have independent study value, and thus has no dedicated trainables. After  3.d4  d5  4.e5  we have reached a transposition to the Advance Variation of the French, covered here. }
3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bc4 Nf6 { Attacking our e4-pawn. } 5. Ng5
{ Defending the pawn and going for the weak f7-pawn. } 5... d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 7.
d4
{ This idea, and in fact the whole position, is akin to the famous Two Knights Attack variation: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Bc4  Nf6  4.Ng5  d5  5.exd5  Nxd5  . }
7... cxd4 8. O-O Be7 9. Nxf7 { Boom! } 9... Kxf7 10. Qf3+ Ke6 11. a4
{ This absolutely shocking move is the key to retaining our attack. Amazingly, White gets away with this 'time-wasting' move whose sole purpose is to provide a safe shelter for the c4-bishop after Black plays Na5. Now Black can't disentangle themselves from the pin. }
*

