[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... e5
{ This move is actually nowhere near as bad as it looks!   Note that  2...e6  does not have independent study value, and thus has no dedicated trainables. After  3.d4  d5  4.e5  we have reached a transposition to the Advance Variation of the French, covered here. }
3. Nf3 Nc6 4. Bc4 Be7 { Black's safest way to develop the kingside. } 5. d4
cxd4 6. cxd4 exd4 7. Nxd4
{ Having clarified the situation in the center, White now dominates it. } 7...
Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Nc2
{ This apparently unprincipled move is vitally important to retain our advantage! The purpose of the move is to gain control of the d5-square. The knight on c2 can later be re-routed to the d5-outpost via e3.   Instead,  9.O-O  Nxe4!  equalizes for Black:  10.Nxe4  d5  . }
9... Bc5 10. O-O d6 11. Be3
{ White enjoys the upper hand due to our greater piece mobility and the vulnerability of the isolated d6-pawn. White’s plan is to play Qe2 followed by Rfd1, piling up on the weak d6-pawn. Additionally, a2-a3 in combination with b2-b4 is a solid plan to gain space and eliminate the most important defender of the d6-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d6
{ Although some opening books consider this move to be 'tricky', the reality is that it is entirely unprincipled and allows us to gain control of the center without contest. }
3. d4 { The principled response! } 3... Nf6 4. Bd3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. O-O
{ White's development flows undisturbed and Black has limited chances to contest the central pawn formation. }
6... O-O 7. Re1
{ White reinforces the center. This prophylactic move delays the development of the b1-knight on purpose. This is a clever idea because Black often captures on d4, allowing our knight to develop to c3 after the recapture. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4
{ Black hopes to pressure the d4-pawn using this pin and the subsequent ...Nc6. However, this is something we can easily deal with!   8...Nc6  is almost always met by the central thrust:  9.d5  Ne5  10.Nxe5  dxe5  11.Nc3  e6  12.Qb3  exd5  13.exd5  with a pleasant position.  White has a dangerous passed pawn and greater piece mobility. Once Black defends e5, our plans will include Bg5, Rad1, Bc4. }
9. Nbd2
{ This time, the knight is needed on d2 to back up his buddy on f3. This allows our queen to escape the annoying pin. }
9... Nc6 10. h3
{ This move is a good test for Black as going back to h5 means Black has to reckon with giving up a piece after g2-g4. }
10... Bxf3
{ This is the most popular move on a club level, one that immediately yields a sizeable edge to White. }
11. Nxf3 e5 12. d5 Nb4 13. Bb1
{ An important move! White preserves the bishop but also keeps an eye on the c2-square. In this King's Indian-like position, Black is stuck with a bad bishop on g7 @@StartBracket@@walled in behind the d6 and e5-pawns@@EndBracket@@, and is yet to begin the usual kingside attack.  Our plan is to kick the knight with a3, followed by Be3, Bd3, Rc1 with the idea of a queenside attack and penetration along the c-file.   13.Bf1  Rc8  with  the ...Nc2 threat is unpleasant. }
*

