[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d6
{ Although some opening books consider this move to be 'tricky', the reality is that it is entirely unprincipled and allows us to gain control of the center without contest. }
3. d4 { The principled response! } 3... Nf6 4. Bd3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. O-O
{ White's development flows undisturbed and Black has limited chances to contest the central pawn formation. }
6... O-O 7. Re1
{ White reinforces the center. This prophylactic move delays the development of the b1-knight on purpose. This is a clever idea because Black often captures on d4, allowing our knight to develop to c3 after the recapture. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4
{ Black hopes to pressure the d4-pawn using this pin and the subsequent ...Nc6. However, this is something we can easily deal with!   8...Nc6  is almost always met by the central thrust:  9.d5  Ne5  10.Nxe5  dxe5  11.Nc3  e6  12.Qb3  exd5  13.exd5  with a pleasant position.  White has a dangerous passed pawn and greater piece mobility. Once Black defends e5, our plans will include Bg5, Rad1, Bc4. }
9. Nbd2
{ This time, the knight is needed on d2 to back up his buddy on f3. This allows our queen to escape the annoying pin. }
9... Nc6 10. h3
{ This move is a good test for Black as going back to h5 means Black has to reckon with giving up a piece after g2-g4. }
10... Bh5 11. Qa4
{ This move is a novelty compared to the Carlsen - Nepomniachtchi game, where g4 was played immediately. The text allows us to recreate the g2-g4 threat under more favorable circumstances because the queen is no longer in a pin and it also supports the d4-pawn.   11.g4  Nxg4  12.hxg4  Bxg4  with counterplay against the white king was Carlsen - Nepomniachtchi, 2020. }
11... Bxf3 12. Nxf3 Nd7 13. Be3
{ And White retains a firm advantage. Our central domination is entirely uncontested and Black desperately lacks space. Our plan is to counter ...e7-e5 with d4-d5, gaining even more territory. Otherwise, White is happy to proceed with Rac1, a3, b4, etc, gaining more momentum on the queenside. }
*

