[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nc6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the most commonly played move at the club level, which often leads to early opening disasters. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 Nf6
{ This is one of the many times when the knights can be kicked around by central pawn thrusts, something we should always consider a top priority whenever doable. }
5. d5
{ Only this way! It is important to stop the knights from becoming effective blockaders, e.g. after  5.e5?  Nd5   the central pawns have become rigid, and we can no longer hassle the knights. }
5... Ne5 6. f4
{ Now the pawns keep on rolling forward, conquering the entire center and pushing the cavalry back all the way. }
6... Ng6 7. e5 Ng8 8. Nf3 { White's central domination is simply unbearable. }
