[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the most commonly played move at the club level, which often leads to early opening disasters. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 e6
{ This passive move is one very frequently played at the club level. } 5. d5
{ White immediately grabs the initiative by striking in the center and kicking a developed piece. }
5... exd5 6. exd5 Ne5
{ 6...Nce7??  instantly loses to  7.d6  Ng6  8.Qe2+!  and White wins a piece! }
7. Nc3 Bd6
{ This move can't possibly be right as it hinders the development of the queenside. }
8. Nb5 Qe7 9. Qe2
{ This is a very 'ugly' move in return, as it blocks in the f1-bishop. The positives, however, outweigh the negatives as now Nxd6 followed by f4 is a game-winning threat! The following line is rather irrational but nonetheless very good for us! }
9... Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Kxd2
{ White even gives up castling rights in order to cash in on the multiple pending threats: Nc7, d5-d6, f2-f4. }
11... d6
{ Black's only move. If  11...Qb4+  12.Kd1!  and Black can't avoid losing material. }
12. f4 a6 { 12...Ng6??  13.Nc7++- } 13. Nxd6+
{ This move nets an extra pawn to us. } 13... Qxd6 14. Qxe5+ Qxe5 15. fxe5
{ And White comes out on top with extra material and an intimidating central pawn duo. Our next few moves are likely to be d5-d6, Nf3, and Bd3. }
