1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the most commonly played move at the club level, which often leads to early opening disasters. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 e6
{ This passive move is one very frequently played at the club level. } 5. d5
{ White immediately grabs the initiative by striking in the center and kicking a developed piece. }
5... exd5 6. exd5 Ne5
{ 6...Nce7??  instantly loses to  7.d6  Ng6  8.Qe2+!  and White wins a piece! }
7. Nc3 Bd6
{ This move can't possibly be right as it hinders the development of the queenside. }
8. Nb5 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 d6 11. Rc1
{ This is very uncomfortable for Black as now there is no adequate way to stop Nc7. }
11... Kf8 12. Be2
{ With a further Nf3 followed by O-O, White enjoys a long-lasting advantage due to the insecurity of the black king. At times, Qb4 can be very annoying because d6 is difficult to defend. }
