1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nc6
{ This is the most commonly played move at the club level, which often leads to early opening disasters. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. cxd4 d5 5. exd5 Qxd5 6. Nf3 Bg4
{ This is one of the most popular lines according to the lichess database, but it is actually a move that leads to very unpleasant positions for Black. }
7. Nc3
{ Not only is this move the engine's first choice but it is also the most principled and most aggressive! }
7... Bxf3 { Completely forced, other moves are hardly playable. } 8. gxf3 Qxd4
{ The outline of the upcoming positions is already clear: White will have superior development and the bishop pair to boot. In contrast, Black will have to begin the early middlegame with a completely untouched kingside! }
9. Qxd4 Nxd4 10. Nb5
{ This move leads to a tactical skirmish, where the better-developed side @@StartBracket@@us@@EndBracket@@ should always come out on top! }
10... Nxb5 11. Bxb5+ Kd8 12. Ke2
{ A rare case when we refrain from playing for O-O-O. The reason is that our rooks want to be on d1 and c1 and so the king would be blocking the c1-square. }
12... e5 13. Rd1+ Ke7 14. Rd7+ Kf6 15. Bc4 Be7 16. Rxb7
{ White is completely winning with the material advantage and the two bishops. On top of this, the black king is also in an insecure spot. }
