[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ This move challenges the e4-pawn just like the 2...d5 line which is the other most principled response to the Alapin. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3
{ White is no hurry to recapture on d4. In fact, we are happy to jettison a pawn to accelerate our development. }
5... e6 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2
{ Beginning a common maneuver: Qe2-e4-g4. } 9... Nc6 10. Nc3
{ White is happy to provoke the trade of Black's best piece @@StartBracket@@the centralized d5-knight@@EndBracket@@ even at the cost of a structural weakness on c3. }
10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 dxe5 12. dxe5
{ In the resulting position, both sides have their trumps, but what is certain is the fact that it is a lot easier to play with White as our initiative builds naturally. }
12... b6 13. Qe4 Qc7 14. Bd3
{ White's strategy is rather simple: attack the king! } 14... g6 15. Bh6 Rd8
16. Rad1 Bb7 17. Qf4
{ Whilst the position remains balanced, I certainly prefer White's attacking chances, as Black's defense requires utmost precision throughout the whole middlegame!   As a result, statistically, White scores remarkably well in this position.   White’s main plan is to soften up the kingside with h4-h5. Note that we want to avoid too many trades and so Black’s ...Rd7 is best met by Be4, allowing a trade of 1 pair of rooks, but then rejecting the second trade with Re1! After that, our plan remains h2-h4-h5! }
