{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ This move challenges the e4-pawn just like the 2...d5 line which is the other most principled response to the Alapin. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3
{ White is no hurry to recapture on d4. In fact, we are happy to jettison a pawn to accelerate our development. }
5... e6 6. cxd4 d6 7. Bc4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2
{ Beginning a common maneuver: Qe2-e4-g4. } 9... b6
{ The e6-pawn blocks the development of the c8-bishop, so Black wants to fianchetto it. }
10. Rd1 { This move introduces a very unique plan: } 10... Bb7 11. Bxd5
{ This is most surprising, as the light-squared bishop is a treasured attacker in this structure. However, the move is excellent as now Black struggles to withstand the central pressure. }
11... Bxd5 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. d5
{ This reveals the point of both Rd1 and the unusual trade on d5. White increased the pressure and has a very pleasant position. }
