1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ This move challenges the e4-pawn just like the 2...d5 line which is the other most principled response to the Alapin. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3
{ White is no hurry to recapture on d4. In fact, we are happy to jettison a pawn to accelerate our development. }
5... d6 6. Bc4
{ Interestingly, this move is likely going to transpose either into the 5...Nc6 or the 5...e6 line. }
6... dxe5 { 6...e6  7.cxd4  transposes into the 5...e6 line. } 7. Nxe5 e6 8.
cxd4 { The knight on e5 is now well supported by the d4-pawn. } 8... Be7 9. O-O
O-O { Both sides fully developed their kingside. } 10. Nd2
{ This move is my own invention in this less explored variation. The idea is to avoid a potential trade after  10.Nc3  and  instead head for f3 to back up the e5-knight. }
10... Nc6 11. Ndf3 { Mission accomplished. Time for a new one. } 11... Nxe5 12.
dxe5 b6 13. Qd4
{ This is a maneuver to remember! In other lines, you will see that we execute the same idea via e2-e4-g4. The white queen is en-route to the kingside, where it can become a dominant attacker. }
13... Bb7 14. Qg4
{ White has good attacking prospects based on the kingside and a space advantage, while the number of black defenders around the king is limited. }
