1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ This move challenges the e4-pawn just like the 2...d5 line which is the other most principled response to the Alapin. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3
{ White is no hurry to recapture on d4. In fact, we are happy to jettison a pawn to accelerate our development. }
5... d6 6. Bc4
{ Interestingly, this move is likely going to transpose either into the 5...Nc6 or the 5...e6 line. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 dxe5
{ 7...Nc6  8.exd6  transposes to the main line after 5...Nc6. } 8. Nxe5 e6 9.
cxd4 { And we end up in an IQP, a structure the Alapin often features. } 9...
Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. Be3
{ White simply develops their pieces to good squares. } 12... Bf6 13. Nxc6 bxc6
14. Ne4
{ White is better. Apart from the better piece coordination, White also has the c6-pawn as a juicy target to pile up on. Additionally, unlike in most IQP structures, here we also have an outpost on c5. Last but not least, it is difficult for Black to deploy the c8-bishop in a meaningful way. }
