1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ This move challenges the e4-pawn just like the 2...d5 line which is the other most principled response to the Alapin. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3
{ White is no hurry to recapture on d4. In fact, we are happy to jettison a pawn to accelerate our development. }
5... Nc6 6. Bc4 { Once again, we prefer development over recovering material. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 dxc3
{ This is just a touch too greedy. Now White has a very good version of the Smith-Morra Gambit, where the black knights have jumped around meaninglessly. }
8. Nxc3 g6 9. Ng5
{ White is ready to exploit their attacking potential against the helpless Black army. }
9... Nxe5 10. f4 h6 11. fxe5 hxg5 12. O-O
{ Black's position looks awful, with only one piece developed after 12 moves... }
12... e6 13. Ne4
{ The white attack is simply unstoppable. Due to the chronic weakness of the dark squares @@StartBracket@@note the threats of Nd6+ and Nf6+@@EndBracket@@ and the looming Qf3-Qxf7, Black is unable to withstand the pressure.   After  13...Qc7  14.Qd4  ,  the centralized queen nicely lines up with the h8-rook!  14...Nd5  15.Bxd5!  exd5  16.Nf6+  Kd8  17.Bxg5  with a subsequent Nxd5 is terminal. }
