1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... Nf6
{ This move challenges the e4-pawn just like the 2...d5 line which is the other most principled response to the Alapin. }
3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nf3
{ White is no hurry to recapture on d4. In fact, we are happy to jettison a pawn to accelerate our development. }
5... Nc6 6. Bc4 { Once again, we prefer develpment over recovering material. }
6... Nb6 7. Bb3 d5
{ This move is essentially the same as  7...d6  , as we will take the pawn in either case. }
8. exd6 Qxd6 9. O-O
{ True to our chess philosophy, we prefer development and piece mobility to material, so we delay the recapture on d4. }
9... dxc3 10. Nxc3 Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Bg4 12. Be3
{ Despite being a pawn down, White does not mind this endgame at all as our piece activity will certainly lead to the recovery of the invested material. }
12... e6 13. Nb5 { Threatening a fork on c7. } 13... Rc8
{ Defending against the fork at the cost of a pawn. } 14. Nxa7 Nxa7 15. Bxb6
{ And White has the upper hand in the endgame with their superior development. Additionally, the queenside pawn majority offers an easy plan for White. }
