[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black manages to deny White a wide center but at the cost of bringing the queen out too soon! }
4. d4 cxd4 5. cxd4 Nc6 6. Nf3 e5
{ This is a very aggressive attempt by Black to contest the center very early on. }
7. Nc3 Bb4 { Black's only reasonable move. } 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3
{ Thus, White acquires their main trump card: the bishop pair. } 9... e4 10.
Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Ne7 12. Be2 { Just calmly finishing development. } 12... O-O
13. O-O
{ White holds a small but firm advantage due to the bishop pair. White’s most typical piece layout from here on out includes Qa4, Rfd1 and Rac1, aiming to stir the game towards a slightly favorable endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
