[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...d5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black manages to deny White a wide center but at the cost of bringing the queen out too soon! }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is the major junction here. Black has multiple choices, the two most popular ones being Bg4 and e6 but we will have a look at other options, too. }
5... e6 6. Be3
{ This move is an important one to remember! White's idea is to take on c5, and simply keep the extra pawn under the protection of the bishop on e3. This encourages Black to take on d4. }
6... Nc6 7. dxc5
{ The logical follow-up to Be3. Although your engine will tell you that this variation is even, in practice White has a whopping statistical lead. }
7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Ng4 9. b4
{ Now the pawn on c5 keeps being protected, even after the exchange on e3. }
9... Nxe3+ 10. fxe3 a5
{ Black is trying their best to rip the pawn chain apart and it is our number one priority to keep it intact. }
11. Bb5
{ Pinning the knight for now. Also, taking on c6 might come in handy to defend our b4-pawn.  11.a3??  is a blunder:  11...axb4  12.cxb4  Nxb4  . }
11... Bd7 12. a3 axb4 13. Bxc6
{ This intermezzo allows White to keep their extra pawn. } 13... Bxc6 14. cxb4
{ With an extra pawn, White has excellent chances to convert this endgame. } *

