[Round "?"]
[White "6) Alapin Sicilian"]
[Black "Alapin Sicilian: 2...d5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black manages to deny White a wide center but at the cost of bringing the queen out too soon! }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is the major junction here. Black has multiple choices, the two most popular ones being Bg4 and e6 but we will have a look at other options, too. }
5... e6 6. Be3
{ This move is an important one to remember! White's idea is to take on c5, and simply keep the extra pawn under the protection of the bishop on e3. This encourages Black to take on d4. }
6... cxd4 7. cxd4
{ And thus, we end up in the well-known Isolated Queen's Pawn structure, commonly referred to as an IQP. Generally speaking, White's plans in this structure are:   ➜ Avoid trades;  ➜ Fight for control of the d5-square;  ➜ Create an attack against the opponent's king. }
7... Nc6 8. Nc3 { 8.a3  is an alternative to avoid 8...Bb4. } 8... Qd6 9. a3
{ This 'bunny ear' is usually a waste of time. However, in this structure, it is a super important building block. White denies Black their most common blockading maneuver Nb4-d5, which would also harass our bishop once it comes to d3. }
9... Be7 10. Bd3 { The bishop is ideally placed here. } 10... O-O 11. O-O b6
12. Qe2 Bb7 13. Rad1
{ Since the objective is to avoid trades, the seemingly more obvious  13.Rac1  is less accurate, as it would invite trades along the open c-file. This move also adds support to our desired d4-d5 breakthrough. }
13... Rad8 14. Rfe1
{ Whtie has completed development and is ready to rumble! The most common plan from here on is to create a B+Q battery on the b1-h7 diagonal, which will create threats against the black king. }
*

