1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black manages to deny White a wide center but at the cost of bringing the queen out too soon! }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is the major junction here. Black has multiple choices, the two most popular ones being Bg4 and e6 but we will have a look at other options, too. }
5... Nc6 6. Be3
{ This transposes to the 5...e6 line, with the exception of the following line: }
6... Ng4 7. Nbd2
{ White does not mind the Nxe3 capture here, as it comes with several benefits: It strengthens the center and also opens up the f-file on which White can attack later. }
7... cxd4 8. Bc4
{ This type of rapid development, which often leaves Black with insufficient resources if they play carelessly, is a typical scenario in many of the 2...d5 lines. }
8... Qd8 9. cxd4 e6 10. O-O
{ And White's huge lead in development guarantees a sizeable edge. White has many natural moves such Ne4, Qe2, Rad1, etc. to improve their position, while Black has to play catch-up. }
