[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3
{ This move introduces the Alapin Sicilian. While the Open Sicilian should be part of any e4-repertoire, the Alapin serves as a great introduction, as it does not involve such heavy theoretical work. With 2.c3 White signals their desire to grab the whole center with d2-d4. The two most reliable and principled responses by Black both attack the e4-pawn. }
2... d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black manages to deny White a wide center but at the cost of bringing the queen out too soon! }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3
{ This is the major junction here. Black has multiple choices, the two most popular ones being Bg4 and e6 but we will have a look at other options, too. }
5... g6 6. Na3
{ This knight can head to c2 later from where it supports the center, or create threats on b5. }
6... cxd4 7. Bc4 Qe4+ 8. Be3
{ This lovely tactical shot highlights the tactical potential of the white army. }
8... Be6
{ The only move to avoid immediate disaster.   8...dxe3  loses to the spectacular  9.Bxf7+!!  Kxf7  10.Ng5+  .    8...h6  tries to cover the g5-square, but this is just a textbook case of 'out of the frying pan, into the fire'! Ater  9.Bd3  White now wins at least a piece. }
9. Bd3 Qd5 10. Nb5
{ Pressured by White's continuous threats, Black fails to develop harmoniously. }
10... Na6 11. Nbxd4
{ And White is much better. The black king is still far away from castling and the beautifully amassed white army in the center dominates the board. The sight is nothing short of a Picasso painting! }
