[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.2) Alapin Sicilian - Model Games"]
[Black "N. Vlassov - T. Radjabov, EU-ch Internet fin 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. dxc5 Qxc5 7. h3
{ This move can be inserted at pretty much any point as Bxf3 is never really a worry for us. }
7... Bh5 8. Be3 Qc7 9. Na3 a6
{ Via a different move order we are back to our main line. } 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11.
g4 Bg6 12. O-O-O
{ This is a very bold move, that is played quite frequently in this variation. The insecurity of the black king is becoming worrisome. }
12... e6 13. Bf4 Qc8 14. Ne5
{ White is relentless in increasing the pressure, playing the line exactly in the right spirit! }
14... b5
{ Radjabov is playing with fire and his lower-rated opponent is not shying away from the opportunity to strike!   14...Bc5  would have been much better. }
15. Nxb5 { Now Black gets stuck in the pin, with mortal consequences. } 15...
axb5 16. Qxb5 Be4 17. f3 Bd5 18. Rxd5
{ The key idea. The very moment when Black was about to consolidate with Ra5, here comes a deadly blow! }
18... Nxd5 19. Nxc6 { The following sequence is entirely forced: } 19... Qd7
20. Ne5
{ White happily trades the queens, given his 3@@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@ connected passers on the queenside. }
20... Qxb5 21. Bxb5+ Ke7 22. Nc6+ Kf6
{ 22...Kd7  23.Nb4+  Kc8  24.Nxd5  exd5  25.a4  is also depressing for Black. }
23. Be5+
{ In spite of the fact that the queens are gone, the black king is still in mortal danger! }
23... Kg6 24. Bd3+ f5 25. gxf5+ exf5 26. Rg1+ Kh6
{ 26...Kf7  27.Bc4  Ke6  28.Rd1  is also curtains. } 27. Nd4
{ Black is beyond repair, it was time to call it a day... } 27... Ne7 28. Bf4+
Kh5 29. Rg5+ Kh4 30. Ne6 Kxh3 31. Bf1+
{ A rather strange moment to resign. Having played this far, it would have been nice@@StartBracket@@and logical@@EndBracket@@ to allow the checkmate finish with  31.Bf1+  Kh4  32.Bg3  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
