[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.2) Alapin Sicilian - Model Games"]
[Black "J. Palkovi - A. Keatinge Clay, Harkany Ozdi Memorial 1999"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Bc4 Nb6 7. Bb3 d6 8. exd6
Qxd6 9. O-O Be6 10. Bxe6 Qxe6 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4 Rd8 13. Nc3 Qd7 14. Re1 e6
15. Qf3 Be7 16. Qg3
{ Palkovi, a dedicated Alapin expert, plays the opening and the early midgame with perfect accuracy. As so often in the Alapin, the goal is to disturb Black's development and try to prevent castling. }
16... Bf6 17. Ne4 Bxd4
{ 17...Nd5  18.Rd1!  and Black still struggles with completing development as  18...O-O  loses to the thematic  19.Bh6  . }
18. Bf4 f6
{ Or  18...Nd5  19.Bd6  f5  20.Bc5  fxe4  21.Bxd4  O-O  22.Rxe4  Nf6  23.Rf4  Rfe8  24.Qb3  Qd5  25.Bxf6  . }
19. Rad1
{ The 'Morphy Principle' at work again: White has completed development and his pieces are optimally placed, all this at a cost of a pawn - what a bargain! }
19... e5 { 19...O-O  20.Bc7  Rc8  21.Bd6±  and White wins an exchange. } 20.
Rxd4
{ An unfortunate blunder in a winning position! Palkovi felt that tactics were abound, but chose the wrong idea.  The win was there by the less flashy but perfectly sound  20.Be3!  O-O  21.Bxd4  exd4  22.Nc5+-  and again, Black is losing an exchange. This would have been a lovely finish of a perfectly played game, but sometimes chess is a cruel mistress. }
20... Qxd4 21. Qxg7
{ Or  21.Bxe5  fxe5  22.Qxg7  Qxe4  23.Kf1  Qd3+  24.Kg1  Nc4  25.b3  Qg6  26.Qxh8+  Ke7  27.Qxd8+  Kxd8  . }
21... Qxe4
{ And now it is Black who is running away with the win, after a cute tactic! }
22. Rc1 Qg6 23. Qxb7
{ 23.Qxh8  would be embarassing after  23...Ke7  24.Rc7+  Nd7  when White's queen is trapped. }
23... O-O 24. Qxa7 Nc8
{ Despite the negative outcome, I decided to pick this game because the early midgame play by Palkovi was perfect and highly instructive. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) French Defense"]
[Black "French Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense is a slightly passive but certainly very solid opening choice that has been known to be a reliable choice for Black ever since Paul Morphy! }
2. d4 d5
{ There are many ways to play against the French. Among them, the best established are  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  . These variations, however, require a lot of time and effort to master. Our choice is simpler, but nonetheless very exciting! }
3. e5
{ This move introduces the Advance Variation. White immediately grabs the offered space and restricts the black army.   This structure is usually founded on a simple strategy for both sides: Black aims to undermine the center with c7-c5 and f7-f6. White, in turn, tries to retain the center and the pawn chain as best as they can. }
3... c5 4. c3 Qb6
{ This move order trick allows Black to play for the well-known, albeit dubious, plan of trading the bad' French bishop on c8 before completing development. }
5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3
{ 'Weird stuff gets beaten by regular stuff', goes the Chesscoachandras Mantra, and so we proceed with the most natural developing move. }
6... Bb5 7. dxc5
{ This move introduces a clever motif that is very typical in the Advance French. }
7... Bxc5 8. b4
{ It turns out that White can ignore the threat against the f2-pawn! } 8...
Bxf2+ { This loses the bishop. } 9. Ke2 Bxd3+ 10. Qxd3
{ And Black has no remedy against the inevitable Rf1. After capturing the piece, White will complete development by Be3, Na3, etc., and cruise towards victory with the extra piece. Also, note that we can easily tuck the white king away at f1-g1 by castling ‘by hand’. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) French Defense"]
[Black "French Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense is a slightly passive but certainly very solid opening choice that has been known to be a reliable choice for Black ever since Paul Morphy! }
2. d4 d5
{ There are many ways to play against the French. Among them, the best established are  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  . These variations, however, require a lot of time and effort to master. Our choice is simpler, but nonetheless very exciting! }
3. e5
{ This move introduces the Advance Variation. White immediately grabs the offered space and restricts the black army.   This structure is usually founded on a simple strategy for both sides: Black aims to undermine the center with c7-c5 and f7-f6. White, in turn, tries to retain the center and the pawn chain as best as they can. }
3... c5 4. c3 Qb6
{ This move order trick allows Black to play for the well-known, albeit dubious, plan of trading the bad' French bishop on c8 before completing development. }
5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3
{ 'Weird stuff gets beaten by regular stuff', goes the Chesscoachandras Mantra, and so we proceed with the most natural developing move. }
6... Bb5 7. dxc5
{ This move introduces a clever motif that is very typical in the Advance French. }
7... Bxc5 8. b4
{ It turns out that White can ignore the threat against the f2-pawn! } 8...
Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Bf8
{ Black has to accept the fact that they need to rebuild the foundations of their development as  9...Be7  would block the knight on  g8  . }
10. O-O
{ White's remaining developing moves are straightforward, whilst Black is struggling to find harmony. }
10... Ne7 11. Be3 Qc7 12. Na3
{ Just like in the Alapin, here too, the knight is placed better on a3 than on d2, as it has access to the b5-square and supports the c3-c4 break. }
12... a6 13. c4
{ White blasts open the position before Black can finish their development. Right now, Black can’t move the e7-knight without hanging d5. On the other hand, taking on c4 would invite Na3-c4-d6/b6. Additionally, placing our rook on c1 will either yield yet another developing move with a tempo on the black queen or will create extra tension and tactical opportunities on the file. Last but not least, White has the annoying Bc5 available. The idea is to pressure the e7 knight, and, as a result, indirectly the d5-pawn as well!   The game Hansen - Djurhuus went:  13...Nbc6  14.Bc5  White often happily gives up the e-pawn in order to use the open files to expose the uncastled king!  14...Nxe5  15.Nxe5  Qxe5  16.Rfe1  White’s commanding lead in development is rapidly increasing.  16...Qh5  17.Rad1  Rd8  18.Qb3  d4  when  19.Bb6  followed by Qa4 would have led to the complete paralysis of Black's army. }
*

