[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) French Defense"]
[Black "French Defense #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense is a slightly passive but certainly very solid opening choice that has been known to be a reliable choice for Black ever since Paul Morphy! }
2. d4 d5
{ There are many ways to play against the French. Among them, the best established are  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  . These variations, however, require a lot of time and effort to master. Our choice is simpler, but nonetheless very exciting! }
3. e5
{ This move introduces the Advance Variation. White immediately grabs the offered space and restricts the black army.   This structure is usually founded on a simple strategy for both sides: Black aims to undermine the center with c7-c5 and f7-f6. White, in turn, tries to retain the center and the pawn chain as best as they can. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Bd3 Nge7
{ 6...Qb6  transposes to the main line. } 7. O-O cxd4 8. cxd4 Nf5 9. Bxf5
{ We part with the d3-bishop rather reluctantly, but the resulting pawn structure justifies the investment. }
9... exf5 10. Qb3
{ This is the key move, as now the queen is hitting multiple targets. } 10...
Qb6 11. Qxb6 axb6 12. Nc3
{ White is better due to Black's shattered pawn structure. An interesting plan in this position is to play b3 and a4 pawn pushes, securing our queenside pawns and also fixing the weak b6-pawn. We can then aim to play for Bc1-a3, trading Black’s good bishop. Our overarching aim is to trade down to an endgame where Black is stuck with the terrible e6 ‘French Bishop’, which is walled behind pawns fixed on its own color. }
