1. e4 e6
{ The French Defense is a slightly passive but certainly very solid opening choice that has been known to be a reliable choice for Black ever since Paul Morphy! }
2. d4 d5
{ There are many ways to play against the French. Among them, the best established are  3.Nc3  and  3.Nd2  . These variations, however, require a lot of time and effort to master. Our choice is simpler, but nonetheless very exciting! }
3. e5
{ This move introduces the Advance Variation. White immediately grabs the offered space and restricts the black army.   This structure is usually founded on a simple strategy for both sides: Black aims to undermine the center with c7-c5 and f7-f6. White, in turn, tries to retain the center and the pawn chain as best as they can. }
3... c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6
{ This is Black's most thematic move, immediately pressuring the d4-pawn and keeping an eye on b2 as well. }
6. Bd3
{ This cheeky developing move introduces the Milner-Barry Gambit. White opts to develop the bishop to the most appropriate diagonal, however, it comes at the cost of weakening the d4-pawn. }
6... Bd7
{ This developing move indirectly threatens the d4-pawn since now there is no discovered check with Bb5+ after  7.--  cxd4  8.cxd4  Nxd4  9.Nxd4  Qxd4  .   6...c4  is a very common mistake at the club level. Black releases tension in the center and gives White a free hand to develop. In the ensuing, tightly closed position White's kingside attack develops naturally while Black will struggle to find counterplay. }
7. O-O
{ In essence, this is the real gambit move. White jettisons the d4-pawn in order to accelerate development. }
7... cxd4 8. cxd4 Nxd4
{ Black's best choice is to actually accept the gambit. Everything else is inferior. }
9. Nbd2
{ This move keeps things a bit more complicated than the other line with  9.Nxd4  . }
9... Bc5 10. b4
{ With this additional sacrifice White aims to maintain the initiative and keep Black busy. The continuous distractions disallow Black to focus on developing the kingside and securing the king! }
10... Qxb4 { This is well met by... } 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12. Rb1
{ This move is a well-deserved reward for the 10.b4 sacrifice! Not only do we score yet another tempo on developing, but the rook also aims at a very important target, the b7-pawn! Once on b7, the rook becomes a very annoying attacker along the 7th rank! }
12... Qc3 13. Nf3
{ A necessary measure to defend the d3-bishop. The move also introduces White’s kingside intentions, revolving around the attacking setup Ng5-Qh5. }
13... Bb6
{ Although this move secures the b7-pawn, it creates a new, potentially far greater problem for Black: the weakness of the a3-f8 diagonal  (and the d6-square)  , which White can now exploit at will by playing Ba3 at any time! }
14. Rb3 { We push the black forces back. } 14... Qc7 15. Qd2
{ This highly unusual move is justified by the fact that we must involve the queen in the attack. White has fantastic counterplay on the dark squares. Apart from Ba3-d6, White also intends to play Qg5, targeting g7. The engine’s evaluation here is slightly misleading in the sense that Black must play 10-15 perfect @@StartBracket@@and difficult!@@EndBracket@@ moves to stay afloat! }
