[White "7.2) French Defense - Model Games"]
[Black "M. Pap - N. Pushkov, Belgrade 2006"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Bd3 Bd7 7. O-O cxd4 8. cxd4
Nxd4 9. Nbd2 Bc5 10. b4 Qxb4 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12. Rb1 Qc3 13. Nf3 Bb6 14. Qe2
{ Our line here goes with  14.Rb3  , which is a better move. Nonetheless, Pap's choice also keeps the ball in play. Black is still not out of the woods! }
14... h6 15. Bd2 Qc7 16. Rb4
{ Since the third rank is no longer viable, White opts to execute the well-known rook lift on the 4th! The target is the g-file and the kingside pawns. }
16... Ne7 17. Rg4 g6 18. Rc1 Nc6
{ Oddly, this very natural move is actually a slight mistake. Instead, according to the mighty engine, the ugly  18...Qd8  is to be preferred:  19.Rb1  Rc8  20.a4  Nf5  21.Rgb4  Bc6  22.Bxf5  gxf5  23.Nd4  Rg8  24.Bxh6  Qd7  25.Rc1  with a very messy position. }
19. Rh4 O-O-O
{ At first, it looks like Black has secured his king, but actually, the opposite is true: The royalty on c8 is very far from being safe!   19...Rc8  20.Qe1  would have led to immense complications where Black would still have to resolve the problem of the king and the disconnected rooks. }
20. Bb4
{ Bd6 is a really annoying threat and Black would be more than happy to sac an exchange for this bishop. }
20... Be8 21. Qb2
{ White correctly refuses the possibility of winning the exchange, as it would hand over the initiative and give up his best-attacking piece. Instead, White increases the pressure as now the h8-rook is also in the scope of tactical ideas. }
21... Kb8
{ Black underestimates White's tactical chances and blunders under pressure.  21...Rg8  22.Rxh6  would have been better, although even here Black has yet to resolve his problems. }
22. Bd6 { 22.Bd6  Rxd6  23.exd6  and Black loses too much material. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro Kann: 3...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ This move introduces the Caro-Kann Defense, an opening named after two 19th century masters, hailing from England and Austria, respectively. This opening is known for its reliable, sturdy layout and was a preferred choice for many World Champions including Capablanca, Petrosian, and Karpov. }
2. d4
{ As always, when given the chance, we should grab the center with both pawns! }
2... d5 3. Nc3
{ The most thematic response: White develops a piece and retains the central tension. }
3... g6 { This is a combination of the Caro-Kann and the Modern Defense. } 4.
Nf3
{ The most principled move!  4.h3  is the more popular choice but we prefer to stick to principles. }
4... Bg7 5. Bf4 Bg4 6. Be2
{ White keeps developing in the simplest fashion to secure a sizeable lead in all departments. }
6... dxe4 7. Nxe4 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Bxf6 9. c3
{ White has convincing central control, thus clearly better prospects. Note how neither e7-e5 nor c6-c5 is playable and so Black is struggling to contest the white center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro Kann: 4...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This move leads to two very different positions, depending on how Black retakes on f6. }
5. Nxf6+ gxf6
{ With this quirky move Black takes several risks: The pawn chain is broken into three islands @@StartBracket@@instead of two in case of  5...exf6  @@EndBracket@@, kingside castling is very risky due to the semi-open g-file, and last but not least, the central break White aims to accomplish with d4-d5 will create further weaknesses in Black's pawn structure. }
6. Nf3
{ Unlike in the system with exf6, here the knight is well placed on f3, as many of our plans include knight maneuvers via either d4 or h4. }
6... Bg4
{ Against such pins our gut reaction is always to kick the bishop immediately, but here  7.h3?  fails due to the pressure on the d4-pawn:  7...Bxf3  8.Qxf3  Qxd4  and White does not have sufficient play for the pawn. }
7. Be2
{ The text move breaks the pin and prepares to castle kingside.  7.h3?  Bxf3  8.gxf3  breaks our pawn structure. }
7... e6 8. O-O
{ The g-file attack is nothing more than an illusion, Black does not have sufficient development and central presence to successfully launch a kingside attack. White simply carries the most natural developing move to pull ahead. }
8... Qc7 9. c4 Nd7 10. Nh4
{ This unusual move here has multiple benefits: It forces the trade of the light-squared bishops, after which the d4-d5 central break will be particularly effective, and it also offers the kingside a bolstered defense. }
10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 O-O-O 12. d5
{ This central break is the key idea! After the trades, White is hoping the conquer the f5-square and quickly open the central files. }
12... exd5 13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Be3
{ And White has a tremendous attacking position, whilst the black pawn structure also offers multiple strategic targets, in particular, the weak pawns and the f5-outpost. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Caro-Kann"]
[Black "Caro Kann: 4...Nf6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6
{ This move leads to two very different positions, depending on how Black retakes on f6. }
5. Nxf6+ exf6
{ This move is the less ambitious but more reliable one, endorsed by the legendary opening expert Erwin l'Ami. Black entirely gives up the idea of fighting for the center in order to establish an extremely safe and robust layout. }
6. c3
{ This strange move is required before White plays Bd3-Ne2 - the best layout in this pawn structure.  If  6.Nf3  the knight does not stand well here due to the fact that it is restricted by the f6-pawn.   6.Bc4  leads to a famous blunder:  6...Qe7+  7.Ne2??  Qb4+  . }
6... Bd6 7. Bd3
{ White begins developing their pieces to the most natural squares. } 7... O-O
8. Qc2
{ This annoying move forces Black to defend h7 instead of continuing to develop their pieces. }
8... Re8+
{ The rook develops with a tempo, but White also wants to put the knight on e2 anyway, so this is hardly a concern for us. }
9. Ne2 h6
{ This move causes far less problems, White usually achieves a comfortable edge after this. }
10. O-O
{ Just like in the main variation, here too, we prefer to castle on the same side as Black, in order to allow our queenside pawn majority to advance. }
10... Qc7 11. h3
{ The threat against the h2-pawn can't be ignored and the impulsive  11.f4  thrust creates several weaknesses. }
11... Nd7 12. c4 c5 13. Be3
{ White has a clear advantage in every department: We are better-developed, we have superior central control, and our endgame prospects are preferable due to our queenside pawn majority.  After Black trades on d4, we retake with the knight. Then our main aim is to complete development with Rac1, Rfd1, followed by the methodical mobilization of the queenside pawn majority with a3-b4. }
