[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ This line is called the Karpov Variation, named after the World Champion who employed it frequently at the top level. The idea is to offer a trade on f6 without having to compromise the pawn structure. }
5. Ng5
{ An unorthodox move in return. As the c8-bishop has been blocked in, White is trying to generate tactical opportunities on the light squares, in particular on f7 and e6. Black needs to play very precisely to avoid all the pitfalls lurking in the next couple of moves. }
5... Ngf6
{ 5...e6  is also a perfectly sound move that is going to transpose after  6.Bd3  Ngf6  . }
6. Bd3
{ This is the right square for the bishop, as it allows us to retain our Ne6 ideas. }
6... e6 7. N1f3 h6
{ The last moment in which h6 is still a blunder. Amazingly, Garry Kasparov voluntarily chose this move against Deep Blue, hoping to exploit the engine's reluctance to sacrifice pieces for positional compensation. }
8. Nxe6 { This sacrfice still works! } 8... Qe7 9. O-O
{ Turning the e-file pressure into a trap of our own! Black is now forced to retake with the pawn. }
9... fxe6 { 9...Qxe6  loses immediately to  10.Re1  . } 10. Bg6+ Kd8 11. Bf4
{ The immobilisation is complete. Black is busted!  This is how Kasparov lost as Black against 'Deep Blue':  11...b5  12.a4  Bb7  13.Re1  Nd5  14.Bg3  Kc8  15.axb5  cxb5  16.Qd3  Bc6  17.Bf5!  exf5  18.Rxe7  Bxe7  19.c4!  and Kasparov threw in the towel as further material loss is inevitable. 1-0 Deep Blue - Kasparov, New York 1997. }
