[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ This line is called the Karpov Variation, named after the World Champion who employed it frequently at the top level. The idea is to offer a trade on f6 without having to compromise the pawn structure. }
5. Ng5
{ An unorthodox move in return. As the c8-bishop has been blocked in, White is trying to generate tactical opportunities on the light squares, in particular on f7 and e6. Black needs to play very precisely to avoid all the pitfalls lurking in the next couple of moves. }
5... Ngf6
{ 5...e6  is also a perfectly sound move that is going to transpose after  6.Bd3  Ngf6  . }
6. Bd3
{ This is the right square for the bishop, as it allows us to retain our Ne6 ideas. }
6... e6 7. N1f3 Bd6 8. Qe2
{ White is keeping all options open and prepares to castle queenside. } 8... h6
9. Ne4
{ This retreat is necessary now as the e6-sacrifice no longer works due to Black's improved development. }
9... Nxe4 10. Bxe4
{ This is not the main move, however, we should prefer it because there is little to be gained by engaging with the jungle of variations after  10.Qxe4  . }
10... Nf6
{ This leads to a position that is almost identical to the main line: } 11. Bd3
b6 12. Bd2
{ As it is quite common in the Caro-Kann, White is hoping to tuck away their king to the queenside and bring the a1-rook into the game at once! }
12... Bb7 13. O-O-O Qc7 14. Kb1
{ And we have reached a position from which our plans proceed the same way as in the main line. }
