1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ exf6 6. c3 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8.
Qc2 Re8+ 9. Ne2 h5 10. O-O h4 11. h3
{ As discussed in the opening analysis, it is important to disallow h4-h3, which would cause some discomfort around our king. }
11... Nd7 12. Bd2 Nf8 13. Rae1 Be6 14. f4
{ I think I would have preferred to play  14.Nf4  here, with the idea of trying to grab the bishop pair. This said, the text is a perfectly fine move too! }
14... Qc7 15. f5
{ Ivic decides to grab some space and restricts the light-squared bishop as well as the f8-knight. }
15... Bd7 16. c4 b6
{ 16...c5  17.d5!  would give up the e5-square for good, but White's bind is also becoming tighter, allowing White a comfortable edge. }
17. b4
{ When White gets to set their queenside pawns in motion, it usually is a sign that things are going well. }
17... c5 18. dxc5 bxc5 19. b5
{ By taking this way, White has created a weak pawn on c5 and also a very mobile 2 vs 1 majority on the far end of the queenside. On top of this, the d5-square has become ours too! }
19... Nh7 20. Nc3 Ng5
{ 20...Rxe1  21.Rxe1  Be5  22.Nd5  Qd6  23.Bc3  is also better for White. } 21.
Nd5 Bh2+ 22. Kh1 Qd6 23. Rd1
{ By declining the trade, White puts Black in a very awkward spot: The h2-bishop needs protection and Bxg5 followed by f5-f6 is also a dangerous threat. }
23... Be5 24. Bxg5 fxg5 25. f6 Bd4 26. Bh7+ Kh8 27. fxg7+
{ Ivic misses a lovely win by  27.Bg6  Rf8  28.fxg7+  Kxg7  29.Bxf7  Qh6  30.Qe2  Rxf7  31.Rxf7+  Kxf7  32.Qe7+  Kg8  33.Qxd7  Rf8  and if @@StartFEN@@r3r2k/p2b1pp1/3q1PB1/1PpN2p1/2Pb3p/7P/P1Q3P1/3R1R1K b - - 4 27@@EndFEN@@  27...fxg6  28.Qxg6  gxf6  29.Nxf6  Black will have to part with his queen to avoid the immediate disaster! }
27... Kxg7 28. Nf6
{ This is too soon. The patient  28.Bf5!  would have been much cleaner:  28...Bxf5  29.Qxf5  f6  30.Rxd4!  cxd4  31.Nxf6  with complete destruction! }
28... Re5 29. Be4 Rh8 30. Bd5 Be6 31. Ng4 Rxd5 32. cxd5 Bd7 33. Qc1 Rh5
{ Or  33...Re8  34.a4  . } 34. Rxd4 { This move is now decisive. } 34... cxd4
35. Nf6 Rh6 36. Qxg5+ Rg6 37. Nh5+ Kf8 38. Qxh4 Bxb5 39. Rb1 Bc4 40. Rc1 Ba6
