1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. h4 h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. h5
Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bd2 Ngf6 12. O-O-O Be7 13. Qe2 O-O
{ And so, the 'opposite side castling' scenario has occurred. In such cases, speed is of the essence, whoever strikes first is likely to succeed! }
14. Nf1
{ Although we generally dislike backward going moves, in this case, we have to make an exception. The move prepares the super aggressive g2-g4-g5 pawn storm. }
14... c5 15. g4 cxd4
{ 15...Nxg4??  loses instantly to  16.Rg1  Ndf6  17.Ne5!  Nxe5  18.dxe5  . }
16. g5
{ White correctly ignores material considerations and continues his attack. }
16... hxg5 17. Bxg5 Qa5 18. Kb1 e5 19. Ng3
{ The knight returns triumphantly to g3, which now serves as a perfect springboard towards the weakened f5-square. }
19... Rfe8 20. Nf5 Bf8 21. Rdg1
{ White's attack is gaining momentum with every move, the piece majority on the kingside is already overwhelming! }
21... Kh8 22. N3h4 Qd5 23. Ng6+
{ Naturally, White goes in for the kill with his beautifully assembled army. }
23... fxg6 24. hxg6+ Kg8 25. Rh3
{ The disaster along the h-file is inevitable. } 25... Bc5 26. Rgh1 Kf8 27.
Rh8+ Ng8 28. R1h7 d3 29. Rxg7
{ This lovely queen sacrifice puts the icing on the cake! } 29... dxe2 30. Rf7+
{ With mate to follow after  30...Qxf7  31.Bh6+  Qg7  32.Bxg7  . A sensational attack by the Hungarian GM! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8.2) Caro-Kann - Model Games"]
[Black "J. Timman - P. Leko, Tjuchem 1996"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Ng5 e6 7. N1f3 Bd6 8.
Qe2 h6 9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Nf6 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. Bd2 b6 13. O-O-O Bb7 14. Kb1
Rd8
{ This is a slightly offbeat idea here. Caro-Kann aficionados usually prefer  14...O-O-O  instead. }
15. Rhg1
{ Queenside castling is off the cards and so Timman is getting ready for an attack similar to the Papp-Stohl game. }
15... c5 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. a3
{ This 'bunny ear' here is a venomous move as now Bb4 is on the cards! } 17...
a5
{ This move surrenders the b5-square and allows Timman to start a deadly attack.  17...O-O  would have been better, but White could start an attack anyway with  18.g4  . }
18. Be3 Qc7 19. Bb5+ { Black now has only unattractive choices. } 19... Ke7
{ 19...Bc6  20.Nd4  is also extremely unpleasant. } 20. Nd4
{ Center! The knight is really well-placed on d4, not only covering b5 but also hinting at Nf5+ ideas! }
20... Bxh2 { Or  20...g6  21.Rge1  . } 21. Nf5+
{ Timman immediately pulls the trigger, although the calmer  21.Rge1  first would have been good too. }
21... Kf8 22. Rxd8+ Qxd8 23. Rd1 Qc7 24. Bd4
{ Timman plays in the style of the romantic masters of the late 1800s. He is on a hunt, and he dedicates everything to the cause! }
24... e5
{ Relatively best was  24...exf5  25.Bxf6  gxf6  26.Rd7  Qc5  27.Rxb7  when White retains all his trumps and the Black structure is in shambles:  27...Kg7  28.Qe6  Rf8  29.Qxb6  Qd5  30.Qc6  Rd8  31.Ra7  . }
25. Bxb6
{ Timman can't resist the temptation of playing for the crowd. Objectively  25.Bc3  would have won much more easily. After  25...Bf4  26.Qc4  it is all over. Mate can only be avoided at the cost of heavy material losses. }
25... Qxb6 26. Rd6 Qc7 27. Qc4 Qb8 28. Rb6 Qc8 29. Rxb7
{ Again, Timman, goes for ultimate glory, but this was unnecessary. This said, the winning idea is a bit obscure:  29.Bc6!!  Qxf5  @@StartBracket@@or  29...Bxc6  30.Qc5+  Kg8  31.Ne7++-  @@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@5k1r/1b3pp1/1RB2n1p/p3pq2/2Q5/P7/1PP2PPb/1K6 w - - 0 30@@EndFEN@@  30.Rxb7  Qe6  31.Qxe6  fxe6  32.Rb8+  . }
29... Qxb7 30. Nd6 Qe7
{ Leko returns the favor. The amazing  30...Ne4!!  would have turned the tables! }
31. Qc8+ Ne8 32. Nf5 { And now White is truly winning! } 32... h5
{ Or  32...Qe6  33.Bd7  . } 33. Nxe7 Kxe7 34. Qd7+
{ Even if we consider the missed opportunities, it was a fantastic attacking performance by Timman! }
