[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Pirc and Modern"]
[Black "Modern Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ This is the so-called Modern Defense, which very often transitions into the Pirc. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 d5
{ The Gurgenidze system, named after the very talented but also eclectic Georgian Grandmaster. Black's goal is to create a perfect blockade on the white color complex. }
5. e5
{ The most principled choice as it advances in the center and claims more space. }
5... Nh6
{ This is the alternative with a drastically different plan: Black hopes to challenge White's center with f7-f6 and then Nh6-f7. }
6. Nf3
{ White's development pattern is going to be exactly the same as in the main line. }
6... f6 7. Be3
{ This time round, however, queenside castling is far more likely. } 7... Bg4
8. h3
{ Just like in the main Gurgenidze, the pinner needs to go. Generally, it is a wise operation to 'ask the question' every time we get pinned. }
8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 O-O 10. exf6
{ A reluctant surrender of the e-pawn which had to be done in light of the hanging e5-pawn. Hereafter, White will rely on our attacking prospects on the kingside. }
10... exf6 11. O-O-O { Securing the king and preparing the kingside assault. }
11... f5 12. g4
{ White is clearly better due to the rapidly developing kingside initiative, whilst Black has nothing to show on the other wing. White has two plans after completing development with Bd3:  ➜ One is to play for Ne2-g3, then capture on f5 and attack along the open g-file.  ➜ The other is to push g4-g5 and then play on the h-file with h2-h4-h5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
