[White "9) Pirc and Modern"]
[Black "Modern Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ This is the so-called Modern Defense, which very often transitions into the Pirc. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 d5
{ The Gurgenidze system, named after the very talented but also eclectic Georgian Grandmaster. Black's goal is to create a perfect blockade on the white color complex. }
5. e5
{ The most principled choice as it advances in the center and claims more space. }
5... Nh6
{ This is the alternative with a drastically different plan: Black hopes to challenge White's center with f7-f6 and then Nh6-f7. }
6. Nf3
{ White's development pattern is going to be exactly the same as in the main line. }
6... f6 7. Be3
{ This time round, however, queenside castling is far more likely. } 7... O-O
8. h3
{ This move is as much a sign of aggression as a defensive measure. White is intending to challenge Black on the kingside with g2-g4. }
8... fxe5 9. dxe5
{ The preferred recapture results in an asymmetrical structure in which White's kingside majority poses Black the more pressing questions. }
9... e6 10. Qd2
{ White prefers queenside castling and rightly so! The rook is an important piece along the semi-open d-file, and the kingside attack will flow much more freely in the absence of the white king. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O
{ White is clearly better, with our better piece mobility and piece placement. White’s most important threat is to play g2-g4 followed by f4-f5, taking aim at the h6-knight. If Black responds with ...Nf7, we switch plans and go for a rapid attack along the h-file with h4-h5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Pirc and Modern"]
[Black "Modern Defense #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ This is the so-called Modern Defense, which very often transitions into the Pirc. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 d5
{ The Gurgenidze system, named after the very talented but also eclectic Georgian Grandmaster. Black's goal is to create a perfect blockade on the white color complex. }
5. e5
{ The most principled choice as it advances in the center and claims more space. }
5... h5
{ This strange-looking pawn move is designed to secure the f5-square for the black pieces. }
6. Nf3
{ White continues their development in the most standard fashion. As usual, the rule of thumb is: weird stuff gets beaten by standard stuff! Keep that in mind whenever facing odd openings. }
6... Nh6 7. Be3
{ In the spirit of quick development, White is willing to go as far as allowing  7...Nf5  with a tempo! }
7... Bg4
{ Since Black is building a pawn chain on the white squares, it makes perfect sense to exchange the light-squared bishop first @@StartBracket@@the so-called French bishop - as it is common in similar French-type structures@@EndBracket@@. }
8. h3 { Forcing Black to clarify their intentions on the kingside. } 8... Bxf3
9. Qxf3 Nf5 10. Bf2
{ White secures the bishop and also avoids further trades in order to make Black's life more miserable within their limited space. }
10... h4
{ Black has to deny White the g2-g4 break, not only to limit our kingside aggression but also to secure the f5-knight. }
11. Bd3
{ Developing the last piece. White cleverly hints that castling to either side is still on the table. }
11... e6 12. O-O
{ White's goal now is to blow up the center, which can be achieved by a c2-c4 break. }
12... Nd7 13. Ne2 { Preparing c2-c4. } 13... Bf8 14. b3
{ The last preparatory measure and a very important one! White needs to make sure that the d5-square does not become an outpost for the black knights.   14.c4  dxc4  15.Bxc4  Nb6  is very pleasant for Black. }
14... Be7 15. c4 { And White is clearly better in every section of the board. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Pirc and Modern"]
[Black "Modern Defense #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6
{ This is the so-called Modern Defense, which very often transitions into the Pirc. }
2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. Be3
{ With this move, we steer the game towards a familiar setup and encourage Black to transpose back to the Pirc lines with Nf6 or c6. }
4... a6
{ This is the only noteworthy move in this variation that gives the position a different character compared to the Pirc main lines. }
5. Qd2 b5
{ Compared to the Pirc lines where Black plays c6, the a8-h1 diagonal is now open. It gives Black different options. }
6. f3 Bb7 7. g4
{ This move has multiple benefits. It restricts Black's h7-h5 ideas and it also discourages Nf6.  Instead, if  7.h4  h5  8.Nh3  Nf6  9.Ng5  Nbd7  it is unclear how White can accomplish anything on the kingside and in the center. }
7... Nd7 8. O-O-O Ngf6 9. Kb1
{ This prophylactic move secures the queenside. No matter what Black does now, White will have an adequate answer. }
9... c5 10. h4 { White carries out the usual kingside attack. } 10... h5 11. g5
Nh7 12. dxc5 { White can now open up the position favorably. } 12... dxc5
{ The black king gets caught in the middle now. } 13. Nge2
{ White is clearly on top. Securing the king and working around the terrible h7-knight is too much of a burden. White’s main focus is to ensure that the black king remains in the middle. Typically, we would like to proceed with Nc1-b3, pressuring c5, and Bh3, targeting d7. }
