[Black "Pirc Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ Technically speaking, this move followed by g6 introduces the Pirc. That said, there are a huge number of move order tricks available for Black very early on that may confuse the unsuspecting White player. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Note that  3...e5  transposes back to the Philidor Defense after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  c6  . }
4. Be3
{ This bishop move, usually followed by Qd2, is the backbone of our setup. The idea is to trade the g7-bishop via h6. }
4... Bg7 5. Qd2 Ng4
{ A typical idea to hassle the e3-bishop in many openings. In this particular case, it does not work. }
6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 O-O 8. O-O-O
{ If  8.f3  the knight just goes back with  8...Nf6  . } 8... c6 9. f4
{ White no longer wants to play f3. Instead, we aim to conquer the entire center with f4 and kick the knight with h3. }
