1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ Technically speaking, this move followed by g6 introduces the Pirc. That said, there are a huge number of move order tricks available for Black very early on that may confuse the unsuspecting White player. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Note that  3...e5  transposes back to the Philidor Defense after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  c6  . }
4. Be3
{ This bishop move, usually followed by Qd2, is the backbone of our setup. The idea is to trade the g7-bishop via h6. }
4... Bg7 5. Qd2 O-O
{ This move is really asking for trouble. White's attack now unfolds naturally. }
6. f3
{ Taking the g4-square away from Black's knight and supporting a kingside attack. }
6... Nbd7 7. Nge2 c6 8. Bh6 { We want to trade the strong defender on g7. }
8... b5 9. h4 { We start our kingside attack! } 9... b4 10. Nd1
{ Although this move looks like we are undeveloping our knight, it can prove itself to be an asset on the kingside. }
10... Ba6 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. h5 { And White's attack punches through. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
