[Black "Pirc Defense #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ Technically speaking, this move followed by g6 introduces the Pirc. That said, there are a huge number of move order tricks available for Black very early on that may confuse the unsuspecting White player. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Note that  3...e5  transposes back to the Philidor Defense after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  c6  . }
4. Be3
{ This bishop move, usually followed by Qd2, is the backbone of our setup. The idea is to trade the g7-bishop via h6. }
4... Bg7 5. Qd2 c6 6. Bh6
{ This is the main plan, as now after the trade Black will have difficulties with the placement of their king. }
6... Bxh6 7. Qxh6
{ Thus, Black has been deprived of short castling and now development will be far more challenging. }
7... Qa5 8. Bd3
{ Note that the usual queenside castle runs into trouble here:  8.O-O-O  b5  . }
8... c5
{ This is a counter-intuitive move, but it is actually the most popular one at the top level! }
9. d5 c4 { This trick is Black's main idea. } 10. Bxc4 Nxe4 11. Ne2
{ White completes development and defends the c3-knight. } 11... Nd7 12. O-O
{ With a clearly better position for White. } *

