[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6
{ Technically speaking, this move followed by g6 introduces the Pirc. That said, there are a huge number of move order tricks available for Black very early on that may confuse the unsuspecting White player. }
3. Nc3 g6
{ Note that  3...e5  transposes back to the Philidor Defense after  4.Nf3  Nbd7  5.Bc4  Be7  6.O-O  c6  . }
4. Be3
{ This bishop move, usually followed by Qd2, is the backbone of our setup. The idea is to trade the g7-bishop via h6. }
4... c6
{ In my opinion, this is the most clever way for Black to play. The idea is that Black will not lose a tempo by playing Bg7 and then having to take on h6. }
5. Qd2 b5 { Black immediately begins their queenside counter-offensive. } 6.
Bd3
{ In response, White keeps their options open in regard to castling and instead focuses on completing development. }
6... Nbd7 7. Nf3
{ We are threatening the typical e4-e5 break and so Black's options are limited. }
7... e5 8. O-O
{ Here it is tempting to make one of the most commonly occurring positional mistakes by taking with  8.dxe5?   Don't do this! White gives up the center,  and relinquishes the c5-square to the black minor pieces for no return at all. }
8... Bg7 9. a4
{ It is in our interest to generate as much tension as possible, seeing that our army is far better prepared for battle. }
9... exd4 10. Nxd4 b4 11. Na2
{ Black has difficulty hanging on to both c6 and b4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9.2) Pirc and Modern - Model Games"]
[Black "D. Navara - H. Kallio, European Championship 2001"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 Bg7 5. Qd2 Nc6 6. f3 e5 7. Nge2 O-O 8.
O-O-O exd4 9. Nxd4 Re8 10. g4
{ The opposite side castling scenario demands immediate action! White launches a standard attack. }
10... Bd7 11. h4 Ne5 12. Be2
{ This move protects f3 against the c7-c5 push but also connects the rooks. }
12... h5
{ The Finnish GM makes a very common mistake: playing on the side where he is being attacked. His intent is to slow down the attack, but the result is the opposite!   12...c6  would have been more in the spirit of the position, but even here, White's attack is mighty strong:  13.h5  b5  14.Bh6  . }
13. gxh5 Nxh5 14. Bg5 { Now the attack plays itself! } 14... f6 15. Be3 a6 16.
Rhg1 c5 17. Nb3
{ 17.Nf5!!  was a brilliant strike here, with the following spectacular idea:  17...gxf5  18.f4!  Ng4  19.Bxg4  fxg4  20.Qd5+!  Be6  21.Qxh5  and White regains the sacrificed piece whilst his raging attack continues unabated. }
17... c4 18. Nd4 b5 19. f4
{ This simple move removes the defender of the g6-pawn and seals the game for White. }
19... b4 20. fxe5 bxc3 21. Qxc3 fxe5 22. Rxg6
{ White has a wide range of winning moves here. The text is one of the more spectacular ones. }
22... exd4 23. Bxd4 Bf5 24. exf5 Nf4 25. Bxc4+
{ The carnage is complete, Black called it a day. } *

[Event "?"]
