[White "9.2) Pirc and Modern - Model Games"]
[Black "V. Aveskulov - A. Bachmann Schiavo, Dos Heramanas Internet 2009 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 c6 4. f4 d5 5. e5 h5 6. Nf3 Nh6 7. Be3 Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3
9. Qxf3 Nf5 10. Bf2 h4
{ Although Black does manage to create a blockade on the kingside, it still does not quite make up for the lack of space and proper development. }
11. Bd3 e6 12. O-O Nd7 13. Ne2
{ The key idea. White vacates the path for the c-pawn, so that we can create play in the center and the queenside. }
13... Bf8 14. b3 Be7 15. c4 Qa5 16. a3 Qd8 17. Rfc1 Kf8 18. Kh2 Kg7 19. Ng1
{ 19.c5  was already playable, but the text also hints at the idea of a knight re-route to f3, pressuring h4. }
19... Qb6 20. c5
{ White decides to close the center entirely as the very typical b3-b4-b5 plan is virtually unstoppable. }
20... Qd8 21. b4 Qc7 22. a4 b6 23. b5
{ This move leads to wild complications, which , of course, favors the better developed side... }
23... bxc5 24. dxc5 cxb5 25. axb5 Bxc5 26. Bxf5 gxf5 27. Rxc5
{ This clever move was the idea behind the mass of trades: White gets ahead in material. }
27... Nxc5 28. Rc1
{ The point of White's operation. Black can't escape from the pin. } 28... Rac8
29. Rxc5 Qb7 30. Rxc8 Qxc8 31. Bxa7 Qb7 32. Bc5 Qxb5 33. Be7 Kg6 34. Bf6 Rh7
35. Bxh4 { A lovely final tactic. The bishop is untouchable. } 35... Kg7
{ Or  35...Rxh4  36.Qg3+  Kh5  37.Qg5  . } 36. Bf6+ Kf8 37. Qc3 Qc4 38. Qa3+
Ke8 39. Qe7# { A strategic masterpiece with a lovely tactical finish. } *

