1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. Nc3 g6 4. Be3 c6 5. Qd2 b5 6. Bd3 Nbd7 7. Nf3 e5 8. O-O
Bb7 9. Ne2
{ The other trendy move here is  9.dxe5  , but I prefer Ganguly's choice as it is aiming to fortify White's center with c2-c3, rather than giving it up. }
9... Be7 10. c3 O-O 11. h3 Re8 12. Ng3
{ The position is largely reminiscent of a Ruy Lopez Breyer variation. White can create plans on either side. Ganguly opts for kingside aggression. }
12... Bf8 13. Bg5 Qb6 14. Bc2 Bg7 15. Bh6 Bh8 16. Nf5
{ A well-known motif in this structure. The knight is immune to capture and although it does not threaten anything immediately, its presence is more intimidating. }
16... d5 { 16...gxf5  17.Qg5+  forces checkmate. } 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5
19. Be3
{ 19.Bf4!  seems to be even more promising:  19...Re6  20.e5  Ne4  21.Bxe4  dxe4  22.Nh6+  Kg7  23.Rad1  with a vicious attack against the disjointed black army. }
19... c5 20. Nh6+ Kg7 21. b4
{ Black is getting ripped apart in every part of the board! } 21... dxe4 22.
bxc5 Rxc5 { 22...Qd8  23.Bd4  was hardly better for Black. } 23. Bb3 Bd5 24.
Nf5+ { The pesky knight really makes its presence felt. } 24... Kf8 25. Bxc5+
Qxc5 26. Qh6+ Kg8 27. Qg5 { Ganguly mops up the rest without any issues. }
27... Rc8 28. Bxd5 Nxd5 29. Rad1 Bf6 30. Nh6+ Kg7 31. Qxd5 Qxd5 32. Rxd5 Kxh6
33. Rxb5 Rxc3 34. Rb7 Bd4 35. Rxf7 Rc2 36. Re1 Rc4 37. Re2 Bc5 38. g3 g5 39.
Kg2 Kg6 40. Rc7 h5 41. Rb2 *

