1. e4 d6 2. d4 Nf6 3. f3 { B00 Lion Defense: Lion's Jaw. } 3... g6 4. Be3 Bg7
5. Nc3 O-O 6. Qd2 e5 7. Nge2 exd4 8. Nxd4 d5
{ In order to avoid a deadly kingside attack, Black often opts for this central counterpunch. }
9. e5
{ This is the correct response! In the resulting position, White's kingside trumps will remain the dominant factors. }
9... Ne8 10. Bg5
{ This tempo on the queen allows us to remove a minor piece from the coming c7-c5 and d5-d4 pushes. }
10... Qd7 11. f4
{ This move bolsters the e5-pawn and also allows the d4-knight to jump back to f3 in case of c5. White is clearly ahead already. }
11... b6 12. O-O-O Bb7 13. Nf3 c6 14. Bd3
{ A good time to take stock: White has completed development and is ready to attack. Black, in strong contrast, has an utterly disorganized and underdeveloped army. }
14... f5
{ 14...Na6  would allow a complete wipeout on the kingside:  15.h4!  h6  16.h5!!  hxg5  17.h6  and White regains the piece with a mate attack, since  17...Bh8  loses to  18.h7+  Kg7  19.f5  . }
15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Rhe1
{ Black's position is essentially hopeless after 16 moves, not an everyday sight between two grandmasters. }
16... Na6 17. f5 { White continues his relentless attack. } 17... gxf5 18. Ne5
Qc8 19. Bh6 Ne4
{ This move accelerates Black's fate but the alternatives were hopeless too:  19...Ne8  20.g4!  fxg4  21.Bxg7  Nxg7  22.Qh6!  with an irresistible attack against the black King. }
20. Nxe4 fxe4 21. Rxe4
{ This spectacular sacrifice is a worthy finish to a lovely game! } 21... Qe6
{ Or  21...dxe4  22.Bc4+  Kh8  23.Bxg7+  Kxg7  24.Qg5+  Kh8  25.Ng6+  hxg6  26.Qh6  . }
22. Rg4 Qxe5 23. Bxg7 Qxg7 24. Rxg7+ Kxg7
{ And without waiting for White's next move, Black decided to call it a day. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Scandinavian "]
[Black "Scandinavian: 2...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ This move introduces the  Portuguese Gambit, which is a popular choice of many club-level players. }
3. d4
{ White simply gets on with their usual agendas  @@StartBracket@@center and development@@EndBracket@@, instead of trying to keep the d5-pawn, which can indeed lead to some really unpleasant and complicated scenarios. }
3... Bg4
{ This is the move of the gambiteers, who are trying to trigger the f2-f3 push but of course, this is is not what we will do! }
4. Bb5+
{ This in-between check is a vitally important move in this line. Black is now more or less forced to block with their knight, which is exactly what we want.  In order to understand this, let's take a look at the alternative:  4.Be2  Bxe2  5.Qxe2  Qxd5!  6.Nf3  Qf5!  and now Black has an easy game, with the black queen well out of harm's way. }
4... Nbd7 5. Be2 Bxe2 6. Qxe2
{ In contrast, Black now is forced to take on d5 with the knight, allowing us the conquer the middle of the board without any problems at all! }
6... Nxd5 7. c4 N5f6 8. Nf3
{ White is already clearly better as Black has no central presence at all. }
8... e6 9. Nc3 Bb4 10. Bd2
{ White has fantastic central control provided by the d4 and c4-pawns. As a result, our piece mobility is also greater. Such positions lend themselves to easy ‘natural’ moves, such as O-O, Rad1, Rfe1, a2-a3, Bf4 or Bg5 etc. In strong contrast, it is difficult for Black to find a meaningful way to break out from passivity. }
*

