1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ This move introduces the  Portuguese Gambit, which is a popular choice of many club-level players. }
3. d4
{ White simply gets on with their usual agendas  @@StartBracket@@center and development@@EndBracket@@, instead of trying to keep the d5-pawn, which can indeed lead to some really unpleasant and complicated scenarios. }
3... Nxd5 4. Nf3 Bg4
{ This is the second most commonly played move in this position, but it is not really a good one. The coming c4-c5-Qb3 idea is important to remember! }
5. c4 Nb6 6. c5
{ This thrust is quite commonplace in the 2.Nf6 variations. White surrenders the d5-square in order to launch an offensive on the white squares. }
6... Nd5 7. Qb3
{ Black is already in big trouble. Coordinating the defense of b7 and d5 appears to be very challenging! }
7... Bxf3 8. Qxb7 Nd7 9. gxf3 { White is a pawn up for no compensation! } *

