[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Nf6
{ This move introduces the  Portuguese Gambit, which is a popular choice of many club-level players. }
3. d4
{ White simply gets on with their usual agendas  @@StartBracket@@center and development@@EndBracket@@, instead of trying to keep the d5-pawn, which can indeed lead to some really unpleasant and complicated scenarios. }
3... Nxd5 4. Nf3 g6 5. c4
{ This natural space grab is our bread and butter in this system, allowing us to secure a pleasant space advantage. }
5... Nb6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. c5
{ At first, this move looks like a positional mistake as it hands over the d5-square to Black. Upon deeper analysis, we will see that Black can't keep the d5-square without serious concessions. }
7... Nd5 8. Bc4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. Re1
{ This is a very important move to remember. White ignores the c5-pawn and instead accelerates their development. }
11... bxc5 12. Ng5
{ Although  12.Bg5  is also a good move here, the text is clearly better! All of a sudden, Black has problems holding their position together as both f7 and the a8-rook are subjects of tactical motifs. }
12... e6 13. Qf3 c6 14. Qh3 h6 15. Ne4
{ White has a dominant position with fabulous attacking prospects. } *

