1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 { We immediately attack the queen. } 3... Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5.
Nf3 c6 { 5...Bf5  6.Bd2  c6  transposes. } 6. Bd2
{ We eliminate the pin and create a discovered attack threat against the queen. }
6... Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3
{ We don't mind this exchange at all. It gives us the bishop pair and even allows us to develop our queen with tempo. }
8. Qxf3 Nbd7 9. O-O-O
{ White has all the trumps: better development, superior central control, and the bishop pair. After the prophylactic Kb1, White should consider a kingside expansion with g2-g4-g5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Scandinavian "]
[Black "Scandinavian: 2...Qxd5 3.Nc3 Qa5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 { We immediately attack the queen. } 3... Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5.
Nf3 c6 { 5...Bf5  6.Bd2  c6  transposes. } 6. Bd2
{ We eliminate the pin and create a discovered attack threat against the queen. }
6... Bf5 7. Ne4
{ The idea is to trade on f6 and damage Black's pawn structure. } 7... Qb6 8.
Nxf6+ gxf6 9. b4
{ The most effective way to defend the pawn as it will later become an integral part of our queenside operations. }
9... e6 10. a3 Nd7 11. c4
{ White's central and queenside expansion yields a significant space advantage. Black is lacking a good plan now. }
11... Be7 12. Be2 O-O-O 13. Qa4
{ White's attack will overpower Black's defenses. White’s main threat is c4-c5, indirectly threatening the a7-pawn and also threatening b4-b5, blasting the black king’s defense wide open. Additionally, Bf4 also increases the discomfort of the black king by taking away all the available squares @@StartBracket@@c7-b8@@EndBracket@@ from it. }
