1. e4 d5
{ This move introduces the Scandinavian Defense. In the main line, Black moves their queen out early, which is unprincipled. On that account, we immediately set about exploiting it! }
2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 { We immediately attack the queen. } 3... Qa5 4. d4 Nf6 5.
Nf3 c6 { 5...Bf5  6.Bd2  c6  transposes. } 6. Bd2
{ We eliminate the pin and create a discovered attack threat against the queen. }
6... Bf5 7. Ne4
{ The idea is to trade on f6 and damage Black's pawn structure. } 7... Qc7 8.
Nxf6+ gxf6
{ Just like in the Caro-Kann Nf6 line, here too, Black can take either way, with very similar structures and ideas. }
9. g3 { 9.Bc4  is also popular here but the text offers more. } 9... e6 10. Bg2
Nd7 { Black wants to castle queenside. } 11. O-O Be4
{ This is a very famous trap that even GMs have fallen for! } 12. Re1 f5 13.
Ng5 Bxg2 14. Rxe6+
{ This awesome sacrifice demolishes Black's defense as well as their hopes! }
14... fxe6 15. Qh5+ Kd8 16. Nxe6+ { Game over. } *

