[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10.2) Scandinavian - Model Games"]
[Black "A. Volokitin -  A. N. Cioara, Romanian Championship 2013"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nf3 Qxd5 4. Nc3 Qa5
{ With a slight move order detour, we are now back in the main line Scandinavian. }
5. d4 c6 6. Bd2 Bg4 7. h3 Bh5 8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5
{ This super aggressive setup is our main line for a good reason. Black needs to be extremely careful and accurate as any slight mistake can be fatal. }
9... e6
{ Amazingly, this is already a decisive error!  9...Nbd7  was better. After  10.Nxg6  hxg6  11.g5  Nd5  12.Ne4  Qa4  13.c4  Qxd1+  14.Rxd1  Rh4  15.f3  Nc7  16.Kf2  White has a superior endgame with the two bishops and more space. }
10. h4
{ This motif is worth remembering. The g6-bishop is in great trouble and the h-pawn can't move without creating terrible damage to the structure! }
10... Qb6 { Or  10...h5  11.Nxg6  fxg6  12.Qe2  . } 11. Qe2
{ A typical reaction in such cases. Instead of worrying about the hanging b2-pawn, White also offers the one on c2, but, of course, these pawns are best left untouched! }
11... Bb4
{ 11...Bxc2??  12.Rc1  Qxb2  13.Nc4+-  with huge material losses.   11...Qxb2  12.Rb1  Qxc2  13.Rxb7+-  and White has a huge attack, while the black queen is also very insecure. }
12. O-O-O
{ White naturally completes development, while Black is unable to resolve the problem of the g6-bishop. }
12... Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Be4
{ This is only a temporary success. The bishop on e4 is by no means out of the woods! }
14. Rh3
{ This rook lift is another common motif in these lines. The rook can become very useful on multiple squares on the third rank. }
14... Bd5 15. Be1
{ This shocking retreat decided the game! Black has no defense against the imminent c2-c4. }
15... Bxa2 16. Ra3 Bd5 17. Ba5 Qa6 18. c4
{ The bishop is trapped, the game is over... } 18... b6 19. Bb4 Qb7 20. cxd5
cxd5 21. Bd6 Nbd7 22. Qa6 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
