[White "10.2) Scandinavian - Model Games"]
[Black "Z. Almasi - B. Kurajica, Bled 2002"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 a6 6. g3 b5 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O
e6 9. Bf4 Qb6 10. a4 Bd6 11. Be3 c5
{ Black is now facing a number of threats based on the discovered attack so c5 makes a lot of sense for Black. Apart from the text,  11...O-O  is also playable, but it certainly looks uncomfortable. }
12. axb5 axb5 13. Qe2
{ White's aim is to exploit the loose black pawns on the queenside before Black can complete development. }
13... Rxa1 14. Rxa1 Bxf3 15. dxc5
{ This lovely tactical trick might not be White's best move, but it does retain the advantage for sure!   15.Bxf3  cxd4  16.Qxb5+  Qxb5  17.Nxb5  dxe3  18.Nxd6+  Ke7  19.Nc4  exf2+  20.Kxf2  and White has a great position with the two connected passers on the queenside. }
15... Bxc5 { Or  15...Bxe2  16.cxb6  . } 16. Bxc5 Qxc5 17. Bxf3
{ White has achieved his opening goal: the b5-pawn is chronically weak and the black army is still rather disorganized! }
17... b4 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 O-O 20. Ra4
{ The pawn has wandered off too far from the rest of the pack and is now being hunted down! }
20... b3 21. c3
{ 21.cxb3  was also good:  21...Nd7  22.Kg2  g6  23.b4  Qb6  24.Qc6  Qxc6  25.Bxc6±  . }
21... Nd7 22. Rb4 Qa7 23. Kg2 Nc5 24. Qd4 Qe7 25. Rb5 Rc8 26. Bc6
{ This awesome tactic decides the game in White's favor. } 26... Na6 27. Bb7
Rd8 28. Qe3 Qc7 29. Bxa6 Qc6+ 30. Qf3 Qxa6 31. Rxb3
{ And White, at last, managed to take the pawn that he has been playing against for the last 15 years. Although Almasi's endgame technique is really clean and super educational, I will give the rest without commentary. }
31... h6 32. Ra3 Qc8 33. Ra7 Rf8 34. b4 Qc4 35. Ra8 e5 36. h4 Rxa8 37. Qxa8+
Kh7 38. Qf3 e4 39. Qf5+ g6 40. Qc5 Qd3 41. c4 e3 42. Qxe3 Qxc4 43. Qc5 Qe4+ 44.
Kh2 f5 45. Qa7+ Kg8 46. b5 g5 47. hxg5 hxg5 48. Qe3 Qg4 49. b6 f4 50. Qb3+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
