[White "10.2) Scandinavian - Model Games"]
[Black "I. Zaitsev - N. Vlassov, Moscow 2005"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. Bb5+ Nbd7 5. Be2 Bxe2 6. Qxe2 Nxd5 7. Nf3 g6
8. c4 N5b6 9. Nc3 c6 10. c5
{ 10.O-O  Bg7  11.Bg5  seems even more attractive but the text is certainly good enough too! }
10... Nd5 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. O-O Bg7 13. Re1 e6 14. Bf4 O-O
{ Although Black did manage to castle and complete development, his structure offers little hope. The white queenside pawn majority is already in motion, whereas Black's hopes for an e6-e5 break are essentially non-existent. }
15. b4 a6 16. a4 Qf6 17. Qd2 Qf5
{ Desperate for activity, Black deploys his queen in a rather unusual fashion and indeed, now the royalty has become a target too! }
18. h3 Nf6 19. Rad1 { Not  19.g4??  Nxg4  20.hxg4  Qxg4+∓  . } 19... Ne4 20.
Qe3 Qh5 21. Ng5 { The black queen is running out of air! } 21... Nf6
{ Or  21...Nxg5  22.Bxg5  h6  23.Be7  Rfe8  24.g4+-  . } 22. Nxe6
{ A flashy combination, although the mundane  22.g4  Qh4  23.Kg2  was good too. }
22... fxe6 23. g4 Nxg4 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 25. hxg4 Qh4 26. Bg3 Qd8
{ At the end of the forcing sequence White has a final joke. } 27. Re5
{ That does it. The rook is immune to capture and otherwise the d5-pawn drops. The rest was easy: }
27... Qe8 28. Qxe8 Raxe8 29. Rxd5 Re4 30. g5 Kg8 31. b5 axb5 32. axb5 Rg4 33.
Kg2 Re4 34. Rd7 { And Black had enough! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Alekhine's Defense"]
[Black "Alekhine's Defense #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ This slightly provocative knight jump introduces the Alekhine Defense - named after the 4th World Champion. Black's idea is to provoke an overextension in the center, which they can then undermine. }
2. e5
{ The principled response. If an opponent's knight can be kicked, it is almost always the right response! }
2... Nd5 3. d4 { Centah! When space is offered, we should grab it. } 3... d6 4.
c4
{ The other main theoretical line begins with  4.Nf3  , leading to classical variations. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ The text aims to resolve the battle for the center immediately. Although White does give up the e5-pawn, the d4-c4 formation allows White to remain dominant in the middle. }
5... exd6
{ This leads to a symmetrical pawn structure where White has the upper hand due to our spatial freedom. }
6. Nf3 Bg4
{ Whilst this pin may look annoying, in reality, it accomplishes little, and the bishop can easily become a target. }
7. Nc3
{ Since the pin poses no threats, we can ignore it and continue in a principled fashion by developing our knights first. }
7... Nc6 { Threatening our d4-pawn. } 8. Be3
{ With Nc6 Black has put pressure on the d4-pawn, so this developing move is designed to protect it. }
8... Be7 9. h3
{ This is the issue with early pins! Black does not want to trade the bishop for a knight but the alternatives are hardly any better. }
9... Bh5 10. g4
{ A move that a lot of lower-level players are reluctant to make on account of 'weakening the kingside'. This approach is fundamentally wrong as there is no weakness on the kingside and our king has not castled yet. The truth, in contrast, is that now the black kingside is going to be heavily pressured by the marching pawns. }
10... Bg6 11. d5
{ The black pieces are getting pushed further and further back. } 11... Nb4
{ This move may look intimidating but this is pseudo activity. The knight is soon going to be on the run! }
12. Rc1
{ Black has nothing against the incoming a2-a3, after which their entire army will be in disarray. White dominates the center as well as both wings. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Alekhine's Defense"]
[Black "Alekhine's Defense #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ This slightly provocative knight jump introduces the Alekhine Defense - named after the 4th World Champion. Black's idea is to provoke an overextension in the center, which they can then undermine. }
2. e5
{ The principled response. If an opponent's knight can be kicked, it is almost always the right response! }
2... Nd5 3. d4 { Centah! When space is offered, we should grab it. } 3... d6 4.
c4
{ The other main theoretical line begins with  4.Nf3  , leading to classical variations. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ The text aims to resolve the battle for the center immediately. Although White does give up the e5-pawn, the d4-c4 formation allows White to remain dominant in the middle. }
5... exd6
{ This leads to a symmetrical pawn structure where White has the upper hand due to our spatial freedom. }
6. Nf3 Be7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be2
{ Since Bg4 is likely, the bishop is better placed on e2 as it preemptively breaks the pin, and also keeps the queen's vision of d4 undisturbed. }
8... Bg4 9. O-O Nc6
{ If  9...Bxf3?  then  10.Bxf3  Nxc4??  11.Bxb7  wins the rook. } 10. b3
{ This is a very important detail that is actually a typical motif in many lines of the Alekhine. The idea is to secure the c4-pawn so that it won't hang when we retake on f3 with our bishop. }
10... Bf6 11. Be3
{ Both sides have completed development but White's space advantage and greater piece mobility keep us well ahead. }
11... d5 12. c5 Nc8 { Black is trying to organize play against the d4-pawn. }
13. h3 Bh5 14. b4
{ This aggressive thrust ensures that Black does not achieve their ultimate piece layout. }
14... Nxb4 15. Rb1 a5 { Defending the knight doesn't help. } 16. a3 Nc6 17. g4
{ We insert this active move before taking on b7. } 17... Bg6 18. Rxb7
{ With a clearly better position for White. Both the c7 and d5-pawns are easy targets for White to attack. Thus, Qb3 and Nb5 are our direct threats, depending on Black’s next move. }
*

