15... Bg6 16. Qb3
{ And White hits d5 before Black can develop their attack against d4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) Alekhine's Defense"]
[Black "Alekhine's Defense #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6
{ This slightly provocative knight jump introduces the Alekhine Defense - named after the 4th World Champion. Black's idea is to provoke an overextension in the center, which they can then undermine. }
2. e5
{ The principled response. If an opponent's knight can be kicked, it is almost always the right response! }
2... Nd5 3. d4 { Centah! When space is offered, we should grab it. } 3... d6 4.
c4
{ The other main theoretical line begins with  4.Nf3  , leading to classical variations. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ The text aims to resolve the battle for the center immediately. Although White does give up the e5-pawn, the d4-c4 formation allows White to remain dominant in the middle. }
5... cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3
{ White is following a unique method of development in this line. The idea is to completely mobilize and fortify the queenside in order to prepare for Black's thematic e7-e5 break. }
7... Bg7 8. Rc1
{ White removes the rook from the scope of the g7-bishop. The delayed development of the kingside here is not that pressing as Black is also undeveloped on the queenside. }
8... O-O 9. b3
{ The final step of bolstering the center.  The variation after  9.Nf3  d5  10.c5  Nc4  demonstrates  why the b2-b3 push is necessary. White has to part with one of their bishops. }
9... Bf5
{ 9...Nc6  allows  10.d5!  Remember the mantra: 'When a developed piece can be kicked, it should be kicked!' }
10. Nf3 Nc6 11. d5 Ne5 12. Nd4
{ This demonstrates why this bishop on f5 is almost always misplaced in this variation @@StartBracket@@and more generally in any fianchettoed setups@@EndBracket@@.   After  12...Bd7  13.Be2  ,  White is already threatening to win the game by the piece-winning f2-f4! }
*

