{ This slightly provocative knight jump introduces the Alekhine Defense - named after the 4th World Champion. Black's idea is to provoke an overextension in the center, which they can then undermine. }
2. e5
{ The principled response. If an opponent's knight can be kicked, it is almost always the right response! }
2... Nd5 3. d4 { Centah! When space is offered, we should grab it. } 3... d6 4.
c4
{ The other main theoretical line begins with  4.Nf3  , leading to classical variations. }
4... Nb6 5. exd6
{ The text aims to resolve the battle for the center immediately. Although White does give up the e5-pawn, the d4-c4 formation allows White to remain dominant in the middle. }
5... cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3
{ White is following a unique method of development in this line. The idea is to completely mobilize and fortify the queenside in order to prepare for Black's thematic e7-e5 break. }
7... Bg7 8. Rc1
