[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11.2) Alekhine's Defense - Model Games"]
[Black "Z. Almasi - E. Miroshnichenko, Bundesliga 2004"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1
O-O 9. b3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. c5
{ The key ideas of this variation revolves around this pawn thrust: White wants to use his pawn majority on the queenside, whilst also utilizing the tender d6- and c4-squares. }
12... N6d7 13. Nf3 Nc6 14. Bc4 Na5 15. Be2
{ White's piece coordination is in perfect sync, whereas the black army is disjointed. }
15... Nf8 16. Nb5 Ne6
{ Miroschnichenko tries to employ active measures against the positional pressure. }
17. Nd6 h6
{ 17...Nd4  18.b4  Nac6  19.b5  Na5  20.Nxd4  exd4  21.Bd2  b6  22.Bf3  Rb8  23.c6!!  Rxd6  24.c7  is a lovely line to demonstrate how the positional and tactical ideas often interlink in chess. }
18. O-O Rb8 19. Rfd1
{ Almasi gradually increases the pressure by playing healthy, natural moves. }
19... Nc6 20. Bc4 Bd7 21. Rd2 Na5 22. Bd5
{ When a position is aesthetic in its looks, it is almost always also perfectly sound! This is a textbook case. }
22... Bc6 23. Bxe6 fxe6 24. b4 Bxf3 25. gxf3 Nc6 26. a3
{ Black has managed to trade off some pieces, but at a huge cost: The pawn structure is completely destroyed and the g7-bishop is a passive bystander with no real hopes to join the party! }
26... a6 27. Kf1 Rd7 28. Ke2 Ne7 29. Nc4 Nd5 30. Nb6 Rdd8 31. Rd3
{ Almasi now prepares the next stage: Invasion on the d-file. } 31... Ne7 32.
Rcd1 Nc6 33. Rd6 Bf8 34. Rd7 Re8 35. Rc7 Re7 36. Rxe7 Bxe7 37. Rd7
{ The domination is complete! } 37... Bf8 38. Nc4 e4
{ Or  38...g5  39.Nd6  Rd8  40.Rxb7  Bxd6  41.Rb6  Bxc5  42.Rxc6  Bxe3  43.fxe3  Kf7  44.Rxa6  Rb8  45.Kd3  . }
39. fxe4 g5 40. f3 Bg7 41. h3 Bf6 42. f4
{ And Miroshnichenko has had enough. A positional masterpiece by the Hungarian, who executed his strategy with surgical precision! }
