[Black "Nimzowitsch Defense: 1...Nc6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ This move introduces the Nimzowitsch Defense. A common response at the club level here is  2.Nf3  , hoping to steer the game back towards e4-e5 openings. This, however, is not in line with our principles: When e4 and d4 is allowed, we shall take the center! }
2. d4 e5
{ Yet another invitation to an e4 opening, this time  3.Nf3  would lead to the Scotch. We, however, aim to punish this setup in a more aggressive way. }
3. dxe5 Nxe5 4. Nf3 Nxf3+ 5. gxf3
{ This odd-looking recapture is one of our main plans. White intends to castle queenside and use the semi-open g-file as an avenue of attack.   Black's main problem is that it is hard to see how they can contest White in the center as the d7-d5 break seems extremely difficult to achieve! }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 d5
{ Black tries to change their passive position around by turning it into a gambit. }
7. exd5 Bb4 8. Qe2+ { The key move that secures the advantage for us. } 8...
Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 10. Bd2
{ This move breaks the pin and also prepares to attack on the long diagonal in case of a trade on c3. White managed to retain their extra pawn with a good position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Miscellaneous"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch Defense: 1...Nc6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6
{ This move introduces the Nimzowitsch Defense. A common response at the club level here is  2.Nf3  , hoping to steer the game back towards e4-e5 openings. This, however, is not in line with our principles: When e4 and d4 is allowed, we shall take the center! }
2. d4 d5
{ This is an attempt to transition back into a slightly better version of the Scandinavian Defence, but again, we have other plans! }
3. Nc3 dxe4
{ 3...e5!?  is an attempt to transition back into a slightly better version of the Scandinavian Defense, but again, we have other plans!  4.dxe5  d4  5.Nd5  Nge7  6.Bg5  leaves Black in a cramped position and down material. }
4. d5 Ne5 5. Qd4
{ Although White will lose a few tempi on moving the queen around, the resulting position will prove this maneuver correct. }
5... Ng6 6. Qxe4 Nf6 7. Qa4+
{ White's primary goal is to retain the d5-pawn, which is a 'thorn', disallowing Black to break with e7-e6 or c7-c6 without compromising the structure. }
7... Bd7 8. Bb5 a6 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd7+ Nxd7 11. Nf3
{ White has a comfortable endgame where Black is still struggling with their lack of space and uncoordinated pieces. White wants to castle queenside and put pressure on the e-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Miscellaneous"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1...b6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This is the Owen's Defense, a variation that often leads to inferior French structures for Black. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Nd2
{ This move is not my preferred one but I decided to go with Nd2 to keep your learning simpler.  This said, the truly principled move is  3.Bd3  , and if you fancy an absolutely hair-raising tactical skirmish, I recommend you consider it! Nd2 is our preferred square instead of in order to disallow the Bb4 pin. }
3... e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Ngf3 c5 { This is a very commonly played blunder. } 6. e5
{ White immediately kicks the developed knight, whilst gaining space in the center. }
6... Nd5 7. c4 Nf4 8. Be4 { It turns out that the g2-pawn can't be captured! }
8... Nxg2+
{ 8...Qc7  9.g3  and White dominates the middle and has free development. } 9.
Kf1 Bxe4 10. Nxe4 { And lo and behold, the g2-knight is trapped! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Miscellaneous"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1...b6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This is the Owen's Defense, a variation that often leads to inferior French structures for Black. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Nd2
{ This move is not my preferred one but I decided to go with Nd2 to keep your learning simpler.  This said, the truly principled move is  3.Bd3  , and if you fancy an absolutely hair-raising tactical skirmish, I recommend you consider it! Nd2 is our preferred square instead of in order to disallow the Bb4 pin. }
3... e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Ngf3 d5 6. e5 Nfd7
{ Thus, we have a 'French' structure, where b6-Bb7 was hardly the most useful way to begin development for Black. As a result of those lost tempi, Black now finds it far more challenging to contest the white center than in a regular French. }
7. O-O Ba6
{ This is a common mistake here. Black hopes to trade the bad 'French bishop', but instead gets severely punished in the center! }
8. c4
{ White adjusts their strategy too: since Black keeps on delaying their development @@StartBracket@@two moves with the knight and another two with the bishop@@EndBracket@@, we immediately seek confrontation in the center. }
8... c5 9. Re1 Be7 10. Nf1
{ White is now threatening to take on d5, and Black has no good capture! }
10... Bxc4 { If  10...dxc4  11.Be4  there is no good defense for the a8-rook. }
11. Bxc4 dxc4 12. d5
{ White is winning as  12...exd5  is not possible because it loses the rook to  13.Qxd5  and otherwise, d5-d6 is deadly. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Miscellaneous"]
[Black "Owen's Defense: 1...b6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This is the Owen's Defense, a variation that often leads to inferior French structures for Black. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Nd2
{ This move is not my preferred one but I decided to go with Nd2 to keep your learning simpler.  This said, the truly principled move is  3.Bd3  , and if you fancy an absolutely hair-raising tactical skirmish, I recommend you consider it! Nd2 is our preferred square instead of in order to disallow the Bb4 pin. }
3... e6 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. Ngf3 d5 6. e5 Nfd7
{ Thus, we have a 'French' structure, where b6-Bb7 was hardly the most useful way to begin development for Black. As a result of those lost tempi, Black now finds it far more challenging to contest the white center than in a regular French. }
7. O-O c5 8. c3 Nc6 9. Re1
{ White is preparing the Nd2-f1-g3 maneuver with kingside initiative. } 9...
Be7 10. Nf1
{ This maneuver is worth remembering as it does appear frequently in many other openings, most notably in the Ruy Lopez. White plans to relocate the knight on the kingside to support their plans. }
10... O-O 11. Ng3 Re8 12. Nh5
{ White has a nicely developing kingside attack, while Black has nothing to show on the other wing or in the center. }
*

