[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6
{ This is the Owen's Defense, a variation that often leads to inferior French structures for Black. }
2. d4 Bb7 3. Bd3 f5
{ This move is essentially losing, but the refutation requires us to remember multiple long variations and excellent attacking skills.   3...e6  4.Nd2  transposes into the main line. }
4. exf5 Bxg2 5. Qh5+ g6 6. fxg6 Bg7 7. gxh7+ Kf8 8. Nh3 Nh6 9. Ng5 Bxh1 10. Nc3
Nc6
{ 10...Qe8  loses to  11.Bg6  Qd8  12.Qxh6  Bxh6  13.Ne6+  dxe6  14.Bxh6  . }
11. Bd2 Nxd4 12. O-O-O Bc6 13. Ne6+ Nxe6 14. Bxh6
{ White's attack breaks through. Black is simply unable to deploy the queenside pieces for the defense. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12.2) Miscellaneous - Model Games"]
[Black "E. Torre - B. Larsen, Geneve 1977"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 b6 2. d4 Bb7 3. Nd2 e6 4. Ngf3 c5 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bd3 Nc6
{ This move is double-edged. On the one hand, it obstructs the view of the b7-bishop, on the other hand, it often allows Black to play for Nb4 tricks after a trade on d4. }
7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 Qc7 9. a3
{ This is a dual-purpose move: It stops the Nb4 tricks but also threatens occasionally to gain space on the queenside with b2-b4. }
9... d5
{ 9...d6  10.e5  dxe5  11.dxe5  Nd5  12.Ne4!  Centah! White stands better due to the space advantage and kingside attacking prospects. }
10. e5 Nd7 11. b4 c4
{ A very poor choice, which is a mistake, no matter if it is played by a former world number 3 or an amateur club player! By releasing the tension in the center, Black surrenders himself to a planless, passive position.   11...h6!  was to be preferred, keeping White guessing about potential central breaks and also about the placement of the black king! }
12. Bc2 O-O-O 13. Nf1
{ In closed positions, the respective sides usually play on the side where the pawn chain is 'pointing'. This, in White's case, is the kingside. So even though his king is castled there, White should pursue his plans on that side! }
13... Rdg8 14. Ng5 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 Nf8 16. f4
{ Exactly. In this 'French' structure, White's most common plan is to play for the f4-f5-break, and the placement of the kings does not change this strategy! }
16... h6 17. Bh4 Kb8 18. Ne3 Ne7 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. f5 Qg5 21. Qg4
{ This seems like a slightly rushed decision. There was more fire in the position after  21.Qf3  . }
21... Qxg4 22. Nxg4 exf5 23. Bxf5 Ne6 24. Rf1 Nd8 25. Ne3 Re8 26. Rae1 Rhf8 27.
Bg4
{ This clever adjustment signals the beginning of the end: The maneuver Nf5-d6 is not stoppable without major damage! }
27... Ne6 { 27...g6  28.Rf6  Ne6  29.Ref1  is also terminal. } 28. Nf5 Rd8 29.
Nd6 { White's position is completely winning now. } 29... Ng5 30. h4 Rxd6
{ This move is a clever practical choice, although objectively losing. Larsen, to his credit, tries to stir the pot, but Torre converts without any difficulty.I provide the rest without further commentary. }
31. exd6 Ne4 32. Be6 f6 33. d7 Rd8 34. Re3 Kc7 35. Bf5 Bc6 36. b5 Bxb5 37. Bxe4
dxe4 38. Rxe4 Rxd7 39. Rfe1 Ba4 40. Kf2 a5 41. Re7 h5 42. R1e6 g5 43. hxg5 fxg5
44. Rxd7+ Bxd7 45. Re5 h4 46. Rxg5 h3 47. g4 Bc6 48. Kg3 Bg2 49. Re5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12.2) Miscellaneous - Model Games"]
[Black "J. Barle - R. Knaak, Pula 1975"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 Nc6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. d5 Ne5 5. Qd4 Ng6 6. Qxe4 Nf6 7. Qa4+ Bd7 8.
Bb5 a6 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd7+ Nxd7 11. Nf3 Rd8 12. Be3 Nde5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14.
O-O-O Nc4 15. Bf4 Nd6 16. Rhe1
{ Perfect play so far by the Slovenian IM. Black's position is indeed very depressing, the activation of the kingside looks near impossible! }
16... g6 17. Ne4
{ Another excellent move, trading off Black's only well-placed piece! } 17...
Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Kd7 { 18...Rd7  19.c4  Bg7  20.c5  also looks depressing. } 19.
c4 Bg7 20. c5 Rhe8 21. c6+
{ White decides to go for it, but there was a good case to be made for the patient  21.Kc2  as well. }
21... bxc6 22. Rc4
{ The idea behind the temporary pawn sac; White wants to win both c-pawns and have a '2 vs 1' scenario on the queenside. }
22... c5
{ 22...cxd5  23.Rxd5+  Ke6  24.Ra5!  f5  25.Rxa6+  Kf7  26.Rxc7  is also close to winning for White. }
23. Rxc5 Rc8 24. Rd2 Red8 25. Rdc2
{ White's inspired endgame play is reminiscent of the style of Smyslov and Karpov: Long-lasting squeezing of the weaknesses until the opponent collapses! }
25... Bd4 26. Rxc7+ Rxc7 27. Rxc7+ Ke8 28. d6
{ Another clever shot. Since the d5-pawn's hours were numbered, White forces Black to take it with the e-pawn, creating an isolated pawn for himself! }
28... exd6 29. f3 Rb8 30. b3 Rb6 31. Kd2 a5 32. Kd3
{ All white pieces are more active than their black counterparts, and so, despite material equality, White has great winning chances. }
32... Bc5 33. Bd2 a4 34. Kc4
{ A strange choice here, and the first notable mistake by White!   34.bxa4!  was clearly better with a clear edge. The a-pawn is a menace. }
34... axb3 35. axb3 Bg1 36. h3 d5+ 37. Kc3 Rb5 38. b4 h5 39. Kb3 Rb8
{ After a fair bit of toing and froing @@StartBracket@@likely as a result of serious time trouble@@EndBracket@@, Black collapses under the pressure: }
40. Bg5
{ This move ties down the defense entirely as now Black constantly has to watch out for checkmate threats. White converted easily. }
40... Bb6 41. Re7+ Kf8 42. Rd7 d4 43. Bf6 Ke8 44. Rd5 d3 45. Rxd3 Bc5 46. b5
Bb6 47. Rd5 Bc7 48. Be5 Bxe5 49. Rxe5+ Kd7 50. Rc5 Re8 51. Rc2 Re1 52. Kb4 Rb1+
53. Ka5 g5 54. b6 f5 55. Ka6 Rb3 56. b7 g4 57. hxg4 fxg4 58. fxg4 hxg4 59. Ka7
Ra3+ 60. Kb8 g3 61. Rd2+ Ke6 62. Kc8 *

